# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: artificialization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] This sense of "agricultural land" thus includes a great deal of land not devoted to agricultural use.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The land actually under annually-replanted crops in any given year is instead said to constitute *sown land* or *cropped land*.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] "Permanent cropland" includes forested plantations used to harvest coffee, rubber, or fruit but not tree farms or proper forests used for wood or timber.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Land able to be used for farming is called **cultivable land**.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Farmland, meanwhile, is used variously in reference to all agricultural land, to all cultivable land, or just to the newly restricted sense of "arable land".
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Depending upon its use of artificial irrigation, the FAO's "agricultural land" may be divided into irrigated and non-irrigated land.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] In the context of zoning, *agricultural land* or *agriculturally-zoned land* refers to plots that are permitted to be used for agricultural activities, without regard to its present use or even suitability.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] In some areas, agricultural land is protected so that it can be farmed without any threat of development.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The Agricultural Land Reserve in British Columbia in Canada, for instance, requires approval from its Agricultural Land Commission before its lands can be removed or subdivided.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Under the FAO's definitions above, agricultural land covers 38.4% of the world's land area as of 2011 and in 2023 4.80 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.07 billion ha, compared with 2000.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] In 2011 permanent pastures are 68.4% of all agricultural land (26.3% of global land area), arable land (row crops) is 28.4% of all agricultural land (10.9% of global land area), and permanent crops (e.g. vineyards and orchards) are 3.1% (1.2% of global land area).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] In 2022, the global agricultural land area was 4.78 billion hectares (ha), down from 4.79 billion hectares in 2021.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] In 2023 Asia had the largest share of the global cropland area in 2023 (37%), followed by the Americas (23%), Africa (20%), Europe (18%) and Oceania (2%).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Approximately 30% of global cropland and permanent meadows and pastures can be found in three countries; 12% of global permanent meadows and pastures belonged to China, 10% to Australia and 8% to the United States of America.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Asia had the largest share of the global cropland area in 2021 (37 percent), followed by the Americas (24 percent), Africa (19 percent), Europe (18 percent) and Oceania (2 percent).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] There were differences in cropland expansion in the different regions during this period – Oceania and Africa both had rapid growth in cropland area (33 percent and 27 percent), while Asia and the Americas had more moderate growth (4 percent and 2 percent).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The cropland area of Europe declined between 2000 and 2021 by 5 percent.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] As a result, the cropland area of Africa overtook that of Europe in 2018.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Approximately 30 percent of global cropland and permanent meadows and pastures can be found in three countries.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] In 2021, 12 percent of global permanent meadows and pastures belonged to China, 10 percent to Australia, and 8 percent to the United States of America.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] For the same year, the largest share of global cropland was in India (11 percent), followed by the United States of America (10 percent) and China (8 percent).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Cropland area per capita decreased in all regions between 2000 and 2021 as population increased faster than the cropland area.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The countries with the highest cropland area per capita are Kazakhstan, Australia and Canada, due to vast areas of land available.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Globally, the total amount of permanent pasture according to the FAO has been in decline since 1998, in part due to a decrease of wool production in favor of synthetic fibers (such as polyester) and cotton.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The decrease of permanent pasture, however, does not account for gross conversion (e.g. land extensively cleared for agriculture in some areas, while converted from agriculture to other uses elsewhere) and more detailed analyses have demonstrated this.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] 2015 found that in the United States cropland increased by 2.98 million acres from 2008 to 2012 (comprising 7.34 million acres (29,700 km2) converted to agriculture, and 4.36 million acres (17,600 km2) converted from agriculture).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Prices and rents for agricultural land depend on supply and demand.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Prices/rents rise when the supply of farmland on the market reduces.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Landholders then put more land on the market – causing prices to fall.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Conversely, land prices/rents fall when the demand for agricultural land declines because of falls in the returns from holding and using it.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The immediate triggers for falls in land demand might be reductions in the demand for farm produce or in relevant government subsidies and tax reliefs.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Poor-quality farmland in France and Spain is sold at no lower than €10,000/ha.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The average Russian farm measures 150 hectares (370 acres).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The most prevalent crops in Russia are wheat, barley, corn, rice, sugar beet, soy beans, sunflower, potatoes and vegetables.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Russian farmers harvested roughly 85–90 million tonnes of wheat annually in the years around 2010.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Russia exported most to Egypt, Turkey and Iran in 2012; China was a significant export market as well.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The average yield from the Krasnodar region was between 4 and 5 tonnes per ha, while the Russian average was only 2t/ha.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] The Basic Element Group, a conglomerate owned by Oleg Deripaska, is one of Russia's leading agricultural producers, and owns or manages 109,000ha of Russian farmland, out of 90m actual and 115m total (0.12% actual).
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] In 2013, Ukraine was ranked third in corn production and sixth in wheat production.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] It was the main supplier of corn, wheat, and rape to Europe, although it is unclear whether the internal supply from countries like France were accounted in this calculation.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Ukrainian farmers achieve 60% of the output per unit area of their North American competitors.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] UkrLandFarming PLC produces, from 650,000 hectares (1.6m acres), corn, wheat, barley, sugar beet, and sunflowers.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Until 2014, the chief Ukrainian export terminal was the Crimean port of Sevastopol.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Prime farmland in Illinois is valued, as of August 2018, at $26,000 a hectare.
[src:artificialization/agricultural-land] Average cropland value in the Midwest according to 2020 data from the US Department of Agriculture is $4,607 per acre (about $11,000 per hectare).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] As of 2021, small farms, of which the vast majority are one hectare (about 2.5 acres) or smaller, produce about one-third of the world's food.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Moreover, five of every six farms in the world consist of fewer than 2 hectares (4.9 acres) and take up only around 12% of all agricultural land.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In terms of total land use, large farms are dominant.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] While only 1% of all farms globally are greater than 50 hectares (120 acres), they encompass more than 70% of the world's farmland.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Further, nearly 40% of all global agricultural land is found on farms larger than 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Farms and farming greatly influence rural economics and greatly shape rural society, affecting both the direct agricultural workforce and broader businesses that support the farms and farming populations.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The major agricultural products can be broadly grouped into foods, fibers, fuels, and raw materials (such as rubber and timber).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Food classes include cereals (grains), vegetables, fruits, cooking oils, meat, milk, eggs, and fungi.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Global agricultural production amounts to approximately 11 billion tonnes of food, 32 million tonnes of natural fibers and 4 billion m3 of wood.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] However, around 14% of the world's food is lost from production before reaching the retail level.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers, and technological developments have sharply increased crop yields, but also contributed to ecological and environmental damage.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Selective breeding and modern practices in animal husbandry have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Environmental issues include contributions to climate change, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and other agricultural pollution.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is both a cause of and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation, and climate change, all of which can cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms are widely used, although some countries ban them.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The word *agriculture* is a late Middle English adaptation of Latin *agricultūra*, from *ager* 'field' and *cultūra* 'cultivation' or 'growing'.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, in its broadest sense using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, fiber, forest products, horticultural crops, and their related services".
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, animal husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often excluded.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] It may also be broadly decomposed into **plant agriculture**, which concerns the cultivation of useful plants, and **animal agriculture**, the production of agricultural animals.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] While agriculture usually refers to human activities, other species have been cultivating crops for up to 60 million years, such as some ant (see agriculture in ants), termite and beetle.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The development of agriculture enabled the human population to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centers of origin.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Wild grains were collected and eaten from at least 105,000 years ago.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In the Paleolithic Levant, 23,000 years ago, cereals cultivation of emmer, barley, and oats has been observed near the sea of Galilee.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6200 BC with the earliest known cultivation from 5700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan some 10,500 years ago.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Sorghum was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated in Eurasia.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize (corn) from 10,000 to 6,000 years ago.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The horse was domesticated in the Eurasian Steppes around 3500 BC.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Scholars have offered multiple hypotheses to explain the historical origins of agriculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Studies of the transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural societies indicate an initial period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and the Early Chinese Neolithic in China.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Then, wild stands that had previously been harvested started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to live in villages from about 8000 BC, relying on the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and a canal system for irrigation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2300 BC.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits including dates, grapes, and figs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Ancient Egyptian agriculture relied on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Farming started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and barley, alongside industrial crops such as flax and papyrus.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8000–6000 BC.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Cotton was cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2500 BC in the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In China, from the 5th century BC, there was a nationwide granary system and widespread silk farming.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by irrigation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs had been developed with iron ploughshares and mouldboards.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Asian rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years ago – depending on the molecular clock estimate that is used– on the Pearl River in southern China with a single genetic origin from the wild rice *Oryza rufipogon*.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica (apart from teosinte) include squash, beans, and cacao.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Cocoa was domesticated by the Mayo Chinchipe of the upper Amazon around 3000 BC.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In South America agriculture may have begun about 9000 BC with the domestication of squash (Cucurbita) and other plants.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, tomato, tobacco, and pineapple.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3600 BC.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and *Chenopodium*.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar were harvested.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The domesticated strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding in Europe and North America.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture in loose rotation; a sort of "wild" permaculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] A system of companion planting called the Three Sisters was developed in North America.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The three crops were winter squash, maize, and climbing beans.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practiced systematic burning, possibly to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Scholars have pointed out that hunter-gatherers need a productive environment to support gathering without cultivation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Because the forests of New Guinea have few food plants, early humans may have used "selective burning" to increase the productivity of the wild karuka fruit trees to support the hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The Gunditjmara and other groups developed eel farming and fish trapping systems from some 5,000 years ago.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] There is evidence of 'intensification' across the whole continent over that period.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated yams, native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In the Middle Ages, compared to the Roman period, agriculture in Western Europe became more focused on self-sufficiency.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The agricultural population under feudalism was typically organized into manors consisting of several hundred or more acres of land presided over by a lord of the manor with a Roman Catholic church and priest.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Thanks to the exchange with the Al-Andalus where the Arab Agricultural Revolution was underway, European agriculture transformed, with improved techniques and the diffusion of crop plants, including the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and fruit trees (such as the orange).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] After 1492, the Columbian exchange brought New World crops such as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, rice, and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, sheep and goats) to the Americas.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Irrigation, crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th century with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to rise significantly.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Since 1900, agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Pastoralism involves managing domesticated animals.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In nomadic pastoralism, herds of livestock are moved from place to place in search of pasture, fodder, and water.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced in arid and semi-arid regions of Sahara, Central Asia and some parts of India.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In shifting cultivation, a small area of forest is cleared by cutting and burning the trees.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The cleared land is used for growing crops for a few years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Another patch of land is selected and the process is repeated.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This practice is used in Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon Basin.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy family or local needs alone, with little left over for transport elsewhere.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] It is intensively practiced in Monsoon Asia and South-East Asia.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] An estimated 2.5 billion subsistence farmers worked in 2018, cultivating about 60% of the earth's arable land.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Intensive farming is cultivation to maximize productivity, with a low fallow ratio and a high use of inputs (water, fertilizer, pesticide and automation).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] It is practiced mainly in developed countries.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] From the twentieth century onwards, intensive agriculture increased crop productivity.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, and economic issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically modified organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to alternative approaches such as the organic movement.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Unsustainable farming practices in North America led to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 and began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The growth of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] There are concerns about the lower yield associated with organic farming and its impact on global food security.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] During the 60-year period between 1964 and 2023, most of the increase in agricultural production was achieved through intensification, while the expansion of agricultural land was limited to just 8%.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In the twenty-first century, between 2001 and 2023, global agricultural area decreased by 78 million hectares (Mha) (−2%), with cropland area increasing by 78 Mha and permanent meadows and pastures decreasing by 151 Mha.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] These changes exhibit significant regional variations.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa witnessed cropland expansion of 69 Mha accompanied by 72 Mha of forest loss, while Latin America saw 25 Mha of cropland growth alongside 85 Mha of net forest area loss.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion remains the primary driver of global deforestation, accounting for nearly 90% of forest loss.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In this century, another important aspect to consider is that approximately 3.6 Mha of croplands are abandoned annually, with land degradation likely playing a significant role in these losses.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] By 2015, the agricultural output of China was the largest in the world, followed by the European Union, India and the United States.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture, according to which agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it was in 1948.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agriculture employed 873 million people in 2021, or 27% of the global workforce, 916 million in 2023, compared with 1 027 million (or 40%) in 2000.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The share of agriculture in global GDP was stable at around 4% since 2000–2023.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Despite increases in agricultural production and productivity, between 702 and 828 million people were affected by hunger in 2021.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Food insecurity and malnutrition can be the result of conflict, climate extremes and variability and economic swings.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] It can also be caused by a country's structural characteristics such as income status and natural resource endowments as well as its political economy.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Pesticide use in agriculture went up 62% between 2000 and 2021, with the Americas accounting for half the use in 2021.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and overall food security, given the favorable experience of Vietnam.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agriculture provides about one-quarter of all global employment, more than half in sub-Saharan Africa and almost 60 percent in low-income countries.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] As countries develop, other jobs have historically pulled workers away from agriculture, and labor-saving innovations increase agricultural productivity by reducing labor requirements per unit of output.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Over time, a combination of labor supply and labor demand trends have driven down the share of population employed in agriculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] During the 16th century in Europe, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; by the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] At the start of the 21st century, some one billion people, or over 1/3 of the available work force, were employed in agriculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment of children, and in many countries constitutes the largest percentage of women of any industry.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as the largest global employer in 2007.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In many developed countries, immigrants help fill labor shortages in high-value agriculture activities that are difficult to mechanize.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Foreign farm workers from mostly Eastern Europe, North Africa and South Asia constituted around one-third of the salaried agricultural workforce in Spain, Italy, Greece and Portugal in 2013.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Around the world, women make up a large share of the population employed in agriculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This share is growing in all developing regions except East and Southeast Asia where women already make up about 50 percent of the agricultural workforce.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Women make up 47 percent of the agricultural workforce in sub-Saharan Africa, a rate that has not changed significantly in the past few decades.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Women who work in agricultural production tend to do so under highly unfavorable conditions.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] They tend to be concentrated in the poorest countries, where alternative livelihoods are not available, and they maintain the intensity of their work in conditions of climate-induced weather shocks and in situations of conflict.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Women are less likely to participate as entrepreneurs and independent farmers and are engaged in the production of less lucrative crops.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The gender gap in land productivity between female- and male managed farms of the same size is 24 percent.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] On average, women earn 18.4 percent less than men in wage employment in agriculture; this means that women receive 82 cents for every dollar earned by men.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Progress has been slow in closing gaps in women's access to irrigation and in ownership of livestock, too.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Women in agriculture still have significantly less access than men to inputs, including improved seeds, fertilizers and mechanized equipment.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] On a positive note, the gender gap in access to mobile internet in low- and middle-income countries fell from 25 percent to 16 percent between 2017 and 2021, and the gender gap in access to bank accounts narrowed from 9 to 6 percentage points.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Women are as likely as men to adopt new technologies when the necessary enabling factors are put in place and they have equal access to complementary resources.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agriculture, specifically farming, remains a hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] On industrialized farms, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal agricultural injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can be hazardous to worker health, and workers exposed to pesticides may experience illness or have children with birth defects.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live on the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor accidents, including with all-terrain vehicles.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Occupational fatality data from the last decade indicate that, when looking at all industries, agriculture had the leading number of work-related deaths for youth.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Within this industry, youth between the ages of 10 and 15 suffered the most non-fatal work-related injuries.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] While farming is hazardous, studies have looked at the fact that there are also many benefits to growing up and living on a farm.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The International Labor Organization considers agriculture "one of the most hazardous of all economic sectors".
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] It estimates that the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In addition, incidences of death, injury and illness related to agricultural activities often go unreported.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The organization has developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the prevention of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture should play.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In the United States, agriculture has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda to identify and provide intervention strategies for occupational health and safety issues.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In the European Union, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work has issued guidelines on implementing health and safety directives in agriculture, livestock farming, horticulture, and forestry.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The Agricultural Safety and Health Council of America (ASHCA) also holds a yearly summit to discuss safety.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Extending over 4.8 billion ha in 2025 – the equivalent of one-third of the Earth's land surface – agriculture has a greater impact on land and water resources compared with any other economic sector.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Pressure on land, soil and water resources has seriously compromised the performance and future prospects of agriculture, resulting in further loss of productive land and reduced water availability for farming and other forms of agricultural production.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion drives deforestation and is one of the primary causes of the degradation of carbon-rich ecosystems such as peatlands.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] An estimated 64% of agricultural land is at risk of pesticide pollution, which damages biodiversity by destroying pollinators, harms soil microbiota and makes agrifood systems less resilient to pests, pathogens and climate change.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Accounting for 72% of global freshwater withdrawals, a figure predicted to rise further in the future, agriculture contributes to and is increasingly affected by water scarcity.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Overexploitation of groundwater and seawater intrusion in coastal aquifers is widespread, with major implications for food security.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Overall production varies by country as listed.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Cropping systems vary among farms depending on the available resources and constraints; geography and climate of the farm; government policy; economic, social and political pressures; and the philosophy and culture of the farmer.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Shifting cultivation (or slash and burn) is a system in which forests are burnt, releasing nutrients to support cultivation of annual and then perennial crops for a period of several years.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Then the plot is left fallow to regrow forest, and the farmer moves to a new plot, returning after many more years (10–20).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This fallow period is shortened if population density grows, requiring the input of nutrients (fertilizer or manure) and some manual pest control.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Annual cultivation is the next phase of intensity in which there is no fallow period.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This requires even greater nutrient and pest control inputs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Further industrialization led to the use of monocultures, when one cultivar is planted on a large acreage.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Because of the low biodiversity, nutrient use is uniform and pests tend to build up, necessitating the greater use of pesticides and fertilizers.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Multiple cropping, in which several crops are grown sequentially in one year, and intercropping, when several crops are grown at the same time, are other kinds of annual cropping systems known as polycultures.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In subtropical and arid environments, the timing and extent of agriculture may be limited by rainfall, either not allowing multiple annual crops in a year, or requiring irrigation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In all of these environments perennial crops are grown (coffee, chocolate) and systems are practiced such as agroforestry.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In temperate environments, where ecosystems were predominantly grassland or prairie, highly productive annual farming is the dominant agricultural system.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Important categories of food crops include cereals, legumes, forage, fruits and vegetables.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Natural fibers include cotton, wool, hemp, silk and flax.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Specific crops are cultivated in distinct growing regions throughout the world.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Production is listed in millions of metric tons, based on FAO estimates.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Animal husbandry is the breeding and raising of animals for meat, milk, eggs, or wool, and for work and transport.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Working animals, including horses, mules, oxen, water buffalo, camels, llamas, alpacas, donkeys, and dogs, have for centuries been used to help cultivate fields, harvest crops, wrangle other animals, and transport farm products to buyers.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Livestock production systems can be defined based on feed source, as grassland-based, mixed, and landless.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] As of 2010, 30% of Earth's ice- and water-free area was used for producing livestock, with the sector employing approximately 1.3 billion people.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Between the 1960s and the 2000s, there was a significant increase in livestock production, both by numbers and by carcass weight, especially among beef, pigs and chickens, the latter of which had production increased by almost a factor of 10.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Non-meat animals, such as milk cows and egg-producing chickens, also showed significant production increases.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Global cattle, sheep and goat populations are expected to continue to increase sharply through 2050.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Aquaculture or fish farming, the production of fish for human consumption in confined operations, is one of the fastest growing sectors of food production, growing at an average of 9% a year between 1975 and 2007.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] During the second half of the 20th century, producers using selective breeding focused on creating livestock breeds and crossbreeds that increased production, while mostly disregarding the need to preserve genetic diversity.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This trend has led to a significant decrease in genetic diversity and resources among livestock breeds, leading to a corresponding decrease in disease resistance and local adaptations previously found among traditional breeds.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Grassland based livestock production relies upon plant material such as shrubland, rangeland, and pastures for feeding ruminant animals.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Outside nutrient inputs may be used, however manure is returned directly to the grassland as a major nutrient source.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This system is particularly important in areas where crop production is not feasible because of climate or soil, representing 30–40 million pastoralists.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Mixed production systems use grassland, fodder crops and grain feed crops as feed for ruminant and monogastric (one stomach; mainly chickens and pigs) livestock.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Manure is typically recycled in mixed systems as a fertilizer for crops.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Landless systems rely upon feed from outside the farm, representing the de-linking of crop and livestock production found more prevalently in Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development member countries.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Synthetic fertilizers are more heavily relied upon for crop production and manure use becomes a challenge as well as a source for pollution.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Industrialized countries use these operations to produce much of the global supplies of poultry and pork.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Scientists estimate that 75% of the growth in livestock production between 2003 and 2030 will be in confined animal feeding operations, sometimes called factory farming.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Much of this growth is happening in developing countries in Asia, with much smaller amounts of growth in Africa.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Some of the practices used in commercial livestock production, including the usage of growth hormones, are controversial.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Tillage is the practice of breaking up the soil with tools such as the plow or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Tillage varies in intensity from conventional to no-till.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] It can improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to erosion, triggers the decomposition of organic matter releasing CO2, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, mites, and diseases.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Chemical (pesticides), biological (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and resistance.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Integrated pest management attempts to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides as a last resort.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of use of manure produced by livestock.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Nutrient inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, green manure, compost and minerals.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Crop nutrient use may also be managed using cultural techniques such as crop rotation or a fallow period.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Manure is used either by holding livestock where the feed crop is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, or by spreading either dry or liquid formulations of manure on cropland or pastures.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Water management is needed where rainfall is insufficient or variable, which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Some farmers use irrigation to supplement rainfall.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In other areas such as the Great Plains in the US and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil moisture for the following year.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Recent technological innovations in precision agriculture allow for water status monitoring and automate water usage, leading to more efficient management.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater use worldwide.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] However, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture vary significantly by income level.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In least developed countries and landlocked developing countries, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture are as high as 90 percent of total water withdrawals and about 60 percent in Small Island Developing States.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] According to 2014 report by the International Food Policy Research Institute, agricultural technologies will have the greatest impact on food production if adopted in combination with each other.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Payment for ecosystem services is a method of providing additional incentives to encourage farmers to conserve some aspects of the environment.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Measures might include paying for reforestation upstream of a city, to improve the supply of fresh water.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Different definitions exist for agricultural automation and for the variety of tools and technologies that are used to automate production.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] One view is that agricultural automation refers to autonomous navigation by robots without human intervention.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Alternatively, it is defined as the accomplishment of production tasks through mobile, autonomous, decision-making, mechatronic devices.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] However, FAO finds that these definitions do not capture all the aspects and forms of automation, such as robotic milking machines that are static, most motorized machinery that automates the performing of agricultural operations, and digital tools (e.g., sensors) that automate only diagnosis.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] FAO defines agricultural automation as the use of machinery and equipment in agricultural operations to improve their diagnosis, decision-making or performing, reducing the drudgery of agricultural work or improving the timeliness, and potentially the precision, of agricultural operations.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has involved a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorized mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Precision agriculture often employs such automation technologies.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Motorized machines are increasingly complemented, or even superseded, by new digital equipment that automates diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] A conventional tractor, for example, can be converted into an automated vehicle allowing it to sow a field autonomously.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization has increased significantly across the world in recent years, although reliable global data with broad country coverage exist only for tractors and only up to 2009.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Measuring the overall employment impacts of agricultural automation is difficult because it requires large amounts of data tracking all the transformations and the associated reallocation of workers both upstream and downstream.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] While automation technologies reduce labor needs for the newly automated tasks, they also generate new labor demand for other tasks, such as equipment maintenance and operation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agricultural automation can also stimulate employment by allowing producers to expand production and by creating other agrifood systems jobs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This is especially true when it happens in context of rising scarcity of rural labor, as is the case in high-income countries and many middle-income countries.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] On the other hand, if forcedly promoted, for example through government subsidies in contexts of abundant rural labor, it can lead to labor displacement and falling or stagnant wages, particularly affecting poor and low-skilled workers.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Climate change and agriculture are interrelated on a global scale.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Global warming is already affecting agriculture, with effects unevenly distributed across the world.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In a 2022 report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change describes how human-induced warming has slowed growth of agricultural productivity over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Methane emissions have negatively impacted crop yields by increasing temperatures and surface ozone concentrations.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Warming is also negatively affecting crop and grassland quality and harvest stability.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Ocean warming has decreased sustainable yields of some wild fish populations while ocean acidification and warming have already affected farmed aquatic species.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Climate change will probably increase the risk of food insecurity for some vulnerable groups, such as the poor.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In order to meet the demands of a growing global population, agriculture needs to produce about 50% more food, feed and fibre by 2050 compared with the volumes it generated in 2012, according to estimates by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Achieving such objectives will place additional pressure on the world's already overstretched water, land and soil resources.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands of years, since the beginning of civilization.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger fruits or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to pests.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] His work on dominant and recessive alleles, although initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders a better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable traits, self-pollination and cross-pollination, and molecular techniques that genetically modify the organism.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought tolerance, eased harvest and improved the taste and nutritional value of crop plants.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Plant selection and breeding in the 1920s and 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic engineering) during the 1950s produced the modern commercial varieties of grains such as wheat, corn (maize) and barley.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The Green Revolution popularized the use of conventional hybridization to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties".
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare (t/ha) (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 t/ha in 1990.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] South American average wheat yields are around 2 t/ha, African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up to 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In contrast, the average wheat yield in countries such as France is over 8 t/ha.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, and growth control to avoid lodging).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Investments into innovation for agriculture are long term.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] This is because it takes time for research to become commercialized and for technology to be adapted to meet multiple regions' needs, as well as meet national guidelines before being adopted and planted in a farmer's fields.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] For instance, it took at least 60 years from the introduction of hybrid corn technology before its adoption became widespread.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Agricultural innovation developed for the specific agroecological conditions of one region is not easily transferred and used in another region with different agroecological conditions.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Instead, the innovation would have to be adapted to the specific conditions of that other region and respect its biodiversity and environmental requirements and guidelines.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Some such adaptations can be seen through the steadily increasing number of plant varieties protected under the plant variety protection instrument administered by the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms (GMO) are organisms whose genetic material has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Genetic engineering has expanded the genes available to breeders to use in creating desired germlines for new crops.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Increased durability, nutritional content, insect and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through genetic engineering.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use of GMO foods and crops.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] The Biosafety Protocol, an international treaty, regulates the trade of GMOs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and the EU has had GMO food labeling requirements since 1997.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] As of 2022, the United States requires food containing GMO ingredients to be labeled as well.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-resistant seeds have a gene implanted into their genome that allows the plants to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] These seeds allow the farmer to grow a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] With the increasing use of herbicide-tolerant crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In some areas glyphosate resistant weeds have developed, causing farmers to switch to other herbicides.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to iron deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Other GMO crops used by growers include insect-resistant crops, which have a gene from the soil bacterium *Bacillus thuringiensis* (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] Some believe that similar or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through traditional breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild species.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p01] In some cases, wild species are the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars that have gained resistance to at least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is both a cause of environmental degradation and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation and climate change, which cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is one of the most important drivers of environmental pressures, particularly habitat change, climate change, water use and toxic emissions.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is the main source of toxins released into the environment, including insecticides, especially those used on cotton.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The 2011 UNEP Green Economy report stated that agricultural operations produced some 13 percent of anthropogenic global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] This includes gases from the use of inorganic fertilizers, agro-chemical pesticides, and herbicides, as well as fossil fuel-energy inputs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as pesticide damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of natural environment.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK determined total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 to $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to internalize external costs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted that subsidies also influence the cost of agriculture to society.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture seeks to increase yield and to reduce costs, often employing measures that cut biodiversity to very low levels.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Yield increases with inputs such as fertilizers and removal of pathogens, predators, and competitors (such as weeds).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Costs decrease with increasing scale of farm units, such as making fields larger; this means removing hedges, ditches and other areas of habitat.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Pesticides kill insects, plants and fungi.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Effective yields fall with on-farm losses, which may be caused by poor production practices during harvesting, handling, and storage.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The environmental effects of climate change show that research on pests and diseases that do not generally afflict areas is essential.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] In 2021, farmers discovered stem rust on wheat in the Champagne area of France, a disease that had previously only occurred in Morocco for 20 to 30 years.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Because of climate change, insects that used to die off over the winter are now alive and multiplying.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] A senior UN official, Henning Steinfeld, said that "Livestock are one of the most significant contributors to today's most serious environmental problems".
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Livestock production occupies 70% of all land used for agriculture, or 30% of the land surface of the planet.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] It is one of the largest sources of greenhouse gases, responsible for 18% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions as measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] By comparison, all transportation emits 13.5% of the CO2.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] (This comparison later turned out to be an apples-and-oranges analogy.) It produces 65% of human-related nitrous oxide (which has 296 times the global warming potential of CO2) and 37% of all human-induced methane (which is 23 times as warming as CO2.) It also generates 64% of the ammonia emission.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Livestock expansion is cited as a key factor driving deforestation; in the Amazon basin 70% of previously forested area is now occupied by pastures and the remainder used for feed crops.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Through deforestation and land degradation, livestock is also driving reductions in biodiversity.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] A well documented phenomenon is woody plant encroachment, caused by overgrazing in rangelands.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Land transformation, the use of land to yield goods and services, is the most substantial way humans alter the Earth's ecosystems, and is the driving force causing biodiversity loss.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Estimates of the amount of land transformed by humans vary from 39 to 50%.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] It is estimated that 24% of land globally experiences land degradation, a long-term decline in ecosystem function and productivity, with cropland being disproportionately affected.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Land management is the driving factor behind degradation; 1.5 billion people rely upon the degrading land.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Degradation can be through deforestation, desertification, soil erosion, mineral depletion, acidification, or salinization.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] In 2021, the global agricultural land area was 4.79 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.09 billion ha compared with 2000.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Between 2000 and 2021, roughly two-thirds of agricultural land were used for permanent meadows and pastures (3.21 billion ha in 2021), which declined by 5 percent (0.17 billion ha).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., total agricultural land use is estimated to be 56%, and including grazing, animal agriculture constitutes around 80% of agricultural land.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Eutrophication, excessive nutrient enrichment in aquatic ecosystems resulting in algal blooms and anoxia, leads to fish kills, loss of biodiversity, and renders water unfit for drinking and other industrial uses.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Excessive fertilization and manure application to cropland, as well as high livestock stocking densities cause nutrient (mainly nitrogen and phosphorus) runoff and leaching from agricultural land.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] These nutrients are major nonpoint pollutants contributing to eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems and pollution of groundwater, with harmful effects on human populations.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Fertilizers also reduce terrestrial biodiversity by increasing competition for light, favoring those species that are able to benefit from the added nutrients.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture simultaneously is facing growing freshwater demand and precipitation anomalies (droughts, floods, and extreme rainfall and weather events) on rainfed areas fields and grazing lands.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of withdrawals of freshwater resources, and an estimated 41 percent of current global irrigation water use occurs at the expense of environmental flow requirements.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., agriculture accounts for about 80% of total water consumption, with animal agriculture making up half of agricultural consumption (around 40%).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] It is long known that aquifers in areas as diverse as northern China, the Upper Ganges and the western US are being depleted, and new research extends these problems to aquifers in Iran, Mexico and Saudi Arabia.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Increasing pressure is being placed on water resources by industry and urban areas, meaning that water scarcity is increasing and agriculture is facing the challenge of producing more food for the world's growing population with reduced water resources.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] While industrial withdrawals have declined in the past few decades and municipal withdrawals have increased only marginally since 2010, agricultural withdrawals have continued to grow at an ever faster pace.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agricultural water usage can also cause major environmental problems, including the destruction of natural wetlands, the spread of water-borne diseases, and land degradation through salinization and waterlogging, when irrigation is performed incorrectly.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Pesticide use has increased since 1950 to 2.5 million short tons annually worldwide, yet crop loss from pests has remained relatively constant.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The World Health Organization estimated in 1992 that three million pesticide poisonings occur annually, causing 220,000 deaths.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Pesticides select for pesticide resistance in the pest population, leading to a condition termed the "pesticide treadmill" in which pest resistance warrants the development of a new pesticide.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] An alternative argument is that the way to "save the environment" and prevent famine is by using pesticides and intensive high yield farming, a view exemplified by a quote heading the Center for Global Food Issues website: 'Growing more per acre leaves more land for nature'.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] However, critics argue that a trade-off between the environment and a need for food is not inevitable, and that pesticides can replace good agronomic practices such as crop rotation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The Push–pull agricultural pest management technique involves intercropping, using plant aromas to repel pests from crops (push) and to lure them to a place from which they can then be removed (pull).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture contributes towards climate change through greenhouse gas emissions and by the conversion of non-agricultural land such as forests into agricultural land.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The agriculture, forestry and land use sector contribute between 13% and 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Emissions of nitrous oxide, methane make up over half of total greenhouse gas emission from agriculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Animal husbandry is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Approximately 57% of global GHG emissions from the production of food are from the production of animal-based food while plant-based foods contribute 29% and the remaining 14% is for other utilizations.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Farmland management and land-use change represented major shares of total emissions (38% and 29%, respectively), whereas rice and beef were the largest contributing plant- and animal-based commodities (12% and 25%, respectively).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] South and Southeast Asia and South America were the largest emitters of production-based GHGs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Climate change put significant part of crops in danger already at 1.5 degrees of warming.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] While in North America, Europe and central Asia the share of endangered crops is relatively little at this level of warming, in the Middle east and North Africa region for example, close to 50% of cropland is in danger.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] With further temperature rise the risk increase in all regions, in some more, in some less.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Globally the cropland area in safe climatic zone decrease for all the major crop groups as warming exceed 1.5 degrees.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Current farming methods have resulted in over-stretched water resources, high levels of erosion and reduced soil fertility.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] There is not enough water to continue farming using current practices; therefore how water, land, and ecosystem resources are used to boost crop yields must be reconsidered.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] A solution would be to give value to ecosystems, recognizing environmental and livelihood tradeoffs, and balancing the rights of a variety of users and interests.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Inequities that result when such measures are adopted would need to be addressed, such as the reallocation of water from poor to rich, the clearing of land to make way for more productive farmland, or the preservation of a wetland system that limits fishing rights.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Technological advancements help provide farmers with tools and resources to make farming more sustainable.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Technology permits innovations like conservation tillage, a farming process which helps prevent land loss to erosion, reduces water pollution, and enhances carbon sequestration.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agricultural automation can help address some of the challenges associated with climate change and thus facilitate adaptation efforts.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] For example, the application of digital automation technologies (e.g. in precision agriculture) can improve resource-use efficiency in conditions which are increasingly constrained for agricultural producers.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Moreover, when applied to sensing and early warning, they can help address the uncertainty and unpredictability of weather conditions associated with accelerating climate change.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Other potential sustainable practices include conservation agriculture, agroforestry, improved grazing, avoided grassland conversion, and biochar.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Current mono-crop farming practices in the United States preclude widespread adoption of sustainable practices, such as 2–3 crop rotations that incorporate grass or hay with annual crops, unless negative emission goals such as soil carbon sequestration become policy.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The food demand of Earth's projected population, with current climate change predictions, could be satisfied by improvement of agricultural methods, expansion of agricultural areas, and a sustainability-oriented consumer mindset.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Since the 1940s, agricultural productivity has increased dramatically, due largely to the increased use of energy-intensive mechanization, fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The vast majority of this energy input comes from fossil fuel sources.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the Green Revolution transformed agriculture around the globe, with world grain production increasing significantly (between 70% and 390% for wheat and 60% to 150% for rice, depending on geographic area) as world population doubled.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Heavy reliance on petrochemicals has raised concerns that oil shortages could increase costs and reduce agricultural output.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Industrialized agriculture depends on fossil fuels in two fundamental ways: direct consumption on the farm and manufacture of inputs used on the farm.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Direct consumption includes the use of lubricants and fuels to operate farm vehicles and machinery.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Indirect consumption includes the manufacture of fertilizers, pesticides, and farm machinery.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] In particular, the production of nitrogen fertilizer can account for over half of agricultural energy usage.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Together, direct and indirect consumption by US farms accounts for about 2% of the nation's energy use.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Direct and indirect energy consumption by US farms peaked in 1979, and has since gradually declined.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Food systems encompass not just agriculture but off-farm processing, packaging, transporting, marketing, consumption, and disposal of food and food-related items.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for less than one-fifth of food system energy use in the US.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Plastic products are used extensively in agriculture, including to increase crop yields and improve the efficiency of water and agrichemical use.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] "Agriplastic" products include films to cover greenhouses and tunnels, mulch to cover soil (e.g. to suppress weeds, conserve water, increase soil temperature and aid fertilizer application), shade cloth, pesticide containers, seedling trays, protective mesh and irrigation tubing.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The polymers most commonly used in these products are low-density polyethylene (LPDE), linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The total amount of plastics used in agriculture is difficult to quantify.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] A 2012 study reported that almost 6.5 million tonnes per year were consumed globally while a later study estimated that global demand in 2015 was between 7.3 million and 9 million tonnes.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Widespread use of plastic mulch and lack of systematic collection and management have led to the generation of large amounts of mulch residue.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Weathering and degradation eventually cause the mulch to fragment.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] These fragments and larger pieces of plastic accumulate in soil.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Mulch residue has been measured at levels of 50 to 260 kg per hectare in topsoil in areas where mulch use dates back more than 10 years, which confirms that mulching is a major source of both microplastic and macroplastic soil contamination.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agricultural plastics, especially plastic films, are not easy to recycle because of high contamination levels (up to 40–50% by weight contamination by pesticides, fertilizers, soil and debris, moist vegetation, silage juice water, and UV stabilizers) and collection difficulties .
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Therefore, they are often buried or abandoned in fields and watercourses or burned.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] These disposal practices lead to soil degradation and can result in contamination of soils and leakage of microplastics into the marine environment as a result of precipitation run-off and tidal washing.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] In addition, additives in residual plastic film (such as UV and thermal stabilizers) may have deleterious effects on crop growth, soil structure, nutrient transport and salt levels.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] There is a risk that plastic mulch will deteriorate soil quality, deplete soil organic matter stocks, increase soil water repellence and emit greenhouse gases.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Microplastics released through fragmentation of agricultural plastics can absorb and concentrate contaminants capable of being passed up the trophic chain.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agricultural economics is economics as it relates to the "production, distribution and consumption of [agricultural] goods and services".
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Combining agricultural production with general theories of marketing and business as a discipline of study began in the late 1800s, and grew significantly through the 20th century.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] In the United States, and elsewhere, food costs attributed to food processing, distribution, and agricultural marketing, sometimes referred to as the value chain, have risen while the costs attributed to farming have declined.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] This is related to the greater efficiency of farming, combined with the increased level of value addition (e.g. more highly processed products) provided by the supply chain.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Market concentration has increased in the sector as well, and although the total effect of the increased market concentration is likely increased efficiency, the changes redistribute economic surplus from producers (farmers) and consumers, and may have negative implications for rural communities.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] National government policies, such as taxation, subsidies, tariffs and others, can significantly change the economic marketplace for agricultural products.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Since at least the 1960s, a combination of trade restrictions, exchange rate policies and subsidies have affected farmers in both the developing and the developed world.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] In the 1980s, non-subsidized farmers in developing countries experienced adverse effects from national policies that created artificially low global prices for farm products.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Between the mid-1980s and the early 2000s, several international agreements limited agricultural tariffs, subsidies and other trade restrictions.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] However, as of 2009, there was still a significant amount of policy-driven distortion in global agricultural product prices.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The three agricultural products with the most trade distortion were sugar, milk and rice, mainly due to taxation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Among the oilseeds, sesame had the most taxation, but overall, feed grains and oilseeds had much lower levels of taxation than livestock products.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Since the 1980s, policy-driven distortions have decreases more among livestock products than crops during the worldwide reforms in agricultural policy.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Despite this progress, certain crops, such as cotton, still see subsidies in developed countries artificially deflating global prices, causing hardship in developing countries with non-subsidized farmers.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Unprocessed commodities such as corn, soybeans, and cattle are generally graded to indicate quality, affecting the price the producer receives.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Commodities are generally reported by production quantities, such as volume, number or weight.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agricultural science is a broad multidisciplinary field of biology that encompasses the parts of exact, natural, economic and social sciences used in the practice and understanding of agriculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The scientific study of agriculture began in the 18th century, when Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulphate) as a fertilizer.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Research became more systematic when in 1843, John Lawes and Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term agronomy field experiments at Rothamsted Research Station in England; some of them, such as the Park Grass Experiment, are still running.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] In America, the Hatch Act of 1887 provided funding for what it was the first to call "agricultural science", driven by farmers' interest in fertilizers.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy is the set of government decisions and actions relating to domestic agriculture and imports of foreign agricultural products.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Governments usually implement agricultural policies with the goal of achieving a specific outcome in the domestic agricultural product markets.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy can also touch on food quality, ensuring that the food supply is of a consistent and known quality, food security, ensuring that the food supply meets the population's needs, and conservation.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Policy programs can range from financial programs, such as subsidies, to encouraging producers to enroll in voluntary quality assurance programs.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] A 2021 report finds that globally, support to agricultural producers accounts for almost US$540 billion a year.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] This amounts to 15 percent of total agricultural production value, and is heavily biased towards measures that are leading to inefficiency, as well as are unequally distributed and harmful for the environment and human health.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Crop use in animal agriculture accounts for one form of inefficiency.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Animal agriculture's estimated land use to produce one kilocalorie or gram of protein is 50 to 100 times that of plant-based alternatives.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Furthermore, the larger the livestock, the lower the energy efficiency (kilocalories obtained relative to kilocalories the animal consumes).
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] For instance, beef's energy efficiency is estimated to be 2%.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] There are many influences on the creation of agricultural policy, including consumers, agribusiness, trade lobbies and other groups.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Agribusiness interests hold a large amount of influence over policy making, in the form of lobbying and campaign contributions.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Political action groups, including those interested in environmental issues and labor unions, also provide influence, as do lobbying organizations representing individual agricultural commodities.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) leads international efforts to defeat hunger and provides a forum for the negotiation of global agricultural regulations and agreements.
[src:artificialization/agriculture-p02] Samuel Jutzi, director of FAO's animal production and health division, states that lobbying by large corporations has stopped reforms that would improve human health and the environment.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] An **agriculturist**, **agriculturalist**, **agrologist**, or **agronomist** (abbreviated as **agr.**) is a professional in the science, practice, and management of agriculture and agribusiness.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] It is a regulated profession in Canada, Pakistan, India, Japan, the Philippines, the United States, and the European Union.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Other names used to designate the profession include **agricultural scientist**, **agricultural manager**, **agricultural planner**, **agriculture researcher**, or **agriculture policy maker**.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The primary role of agriculturists are in leading agricultural projects and programs, usually in agribusiness planning or research for the benefit of farms, food, and agribusiness-related organizations.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Agriculturists usually are designated in the government as public agriculturists serving as agriculture policymakers or technical advisors for policy making.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Preparation of technical engineering designs and construction for agriculture meanwhile are reserved for agricultural engineers.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Agriculturists may pursue environmental planning and focus on agricultural and rural planning.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In modern practice, agriculturists are expected to be proficient in digital agriculture such as the use of geographic information systems, artificial intelligence, and remote sensing for better agricultural planning.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Agriculturists of today are involved with many issues, including producing food, creating healthier food, managing the environmental impact of agriculture, distribution of agriculture, recreation surfaces (sports fields, golf courses, and parks), and extracting energy from plants.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Agriculturists often specialize in food and agriculture research areas such as crop rotation, irrigation and drainage, plant breeding, plant physiology, soil classification, soil fertility, weed control, turfgrass and insect and pest control.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In the People's Republic of China, the professional designation is **agricultural technician** **(农业技术员, nóngyè jìshùyuán)**.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] These professionals operate within a state-led agricultural extension system coordinated by the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs (MARA) and are primarily appointed at the county or township level by local government agencies.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Due to the competitive nature of public service employment, individuals who aspire to hold permanent positions within the civil service must pass the National Civil Service Exam (公务员考试).
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In addition to passing this exam, candidates are required to have completed a degree in agriculture or a closely related field and highly-intricate training programs to be eligible for appointment as public agricultural officers.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In India, the professional designation is **Agricultural Scientist** (abbreviated as **ARS**).
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] To qualify for entry level posts, the Agricultural Scientists Recruitment Board conducts competitive examinations pursuant to the Gajendragadkar Report of 1972.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The post of entry level ARS is same with Jr.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The initial pay is fixed after granting advance increments for higher qualification, with PhDs getting the highest salary.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] They are kept on 'tenure track' or 'probation' for two years and upon satisfactory completion of this period they are given tenure and confirmed in the ARS.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] On completing service for designated years and meeting set performance criteria, they are promoted to the next higher grades in a flexible complementation system known as Career Advancement Scheme (CAS).
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Incumbents without a PhD degree are given paid study leave to acquire PhD qualification, which is necessary for career progression.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Through CAS, scientists can rise up to principal scientist grade, which is equivalent to the scale of joint secretary to the Government of India.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The ARS encourages fresh infusion of talent at all senior levels through lateral entry in which incumbent scientists can participate in the open competition and move their career ahead in much shorter time than CAS.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] All the research management positions are filled through open competition.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The director general of ICAR is the highest-ranked member of the ARS, who is *ex officio* secretary to the Government of India, Department of Agricultural Research and Education (DARE), Ministry of Agriculture.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In Japan, the professional designation is agricultural extension officer **(農業指導士, Nōgyō Shidōshi)** by virtue of the Agricultural Improvement Promotion Act.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] One must typically hold a degree in agriculture or a related field, accumulate years of practical technical experience, pass a national qualification exam, and then be appointed by a prefectural government, as guided by standards from the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (MAFF).
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] These officers deliver technical advice, promote good agricultural practices, assist with compliance in programs like the Certified Farm Manager initiative (農業経営士), and support technology transfer to local farmers.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In the Philippines, the official professional designation is **Registered Agriculturist (R.Agr.)** by virtue of the Philippine Agriculturist Act of 2025 or Republic Act No.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Prior to the enactment of the law, the profession has already been regulated by the Professional Regulation Commission and the Professional Board of Agriculture by virtue of Republic Act No.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] A Registered Agriculturist can affix the title "R.Agr." (as name suffix) or "Agr." (as name prefix) to indicate the profession.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The Professional Board of Agriculture was created and established in 2000 by virtue of PRC Resolution No.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] 2000-663 and the first Agriculturist Licensure Examination (ALE) was held in 2003 and has annually been held annually.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Similar to other professions in the Philippines, malpractice and illegal practice of agriculture are grounds for suspension or revocation of certificates of registration and professional licenses.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Licensed agriculturists in the Philippines are integrated into one accredited integrated professional organization, which is the Philippine Association of Agriculturists.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] A separate registry system for farmers, fisherfolk, and agri-youth was established by the Department of Agriculture through the Registry System for Basic Sectors in Agriculture (RSBSA).
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] About 5,500 registered agriculturists pass the licensure examination annually.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] It is one of the hardest licensure examinations in the country with 29.84% passing rate in November 2021.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Professionals and educators with at least five years of experience in agriculture are allowed to be registered as an Agriculturist without taking the licensure examination.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In the European Union, the generic name of the profession is Agronomist/Agricultural Engineer.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The profession is exercised for the public interest in defense of the principles of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union and Directive 2005/36/EC.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In Italy, the professional designation is "Dottori Agronomi" (translated as **Agronomy Doctor**).
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The profession is exercised for the public interest in defense of the principles of Articles 9 and 32 of the Italian Constitution and of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In Canada, the professional designation is "agrologist", also called "*agronome*" in Québec.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] There are more than 10,000 professional agrologists and *agronomes* in Canada.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Professional agrologists are accredited through provincial regulatory bodies, e.g.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] Saskatchewan Institute of Agrology, Nova Scotia Institute of Agrologists.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The requirements to attain professional designation (PAg) are similar in each province.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] A prospective agrologist is typically required to have a four-year undergraduate science degree directly related to agrology.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] If accepted by their provincial institute, the applicant is known as an articling agrologist (AAg) or agrologist-in-training (AIT) and must complete a two-year educational and mentorship program before being considered for a professional designation.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] An alternative certification called "registered technical agrologist" (RTag), or (PTag) is also available, requiring a two-year college or university education in the agricultural sciences instead of a four-year degree.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] These technologists designations require a two-year mentorship and education program, and participate in the same mentorship processes as a professional agrologist.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] In the United States, the professional designation is Certified Professional **Agronomist** (abbreviated **C.PAg**), the American Society of Agronomy is the regulatory organization responsible for certification.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] CPAgs are required to complete at least 50 hours of continuing education through the American Society of Agronomy every two years in order to retain their certification.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The American Society of Agronomy also provides certifications for Certified Crop Advisors (CCA).
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] To become a Certified Crop Adviser an applicant must pass two exams that may both be written on the same day at the same location.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The International exam is written by CCAs in North America.
[src:artificialization/agriculturist] The Prairie region exam is written by individuals wishing to work as advisers in the three Prairie provinces of Canada or in the heartland states of the US.
[src:artificialization/albedo] While directional-hemispherical reflectance factor is calculated for a single angle of incidence (i.e., for a given position of the Sun), albedo is the directional integration of reflectance over all solar angles in a given period.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The temporal resolution may range from seconds (as obtained from flux measurements) to daily, monthly, or annual averages.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Unless given for a specific wavelength (spectral albedo), albedo refers to the entire spectrum of solar radiation.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Due to measurement constraints, it is often given for the spectrum in which most solar energy reaches the surface (between 0.3 and 3 μm).
[src:artificialization/albedo] This spectrum includes visible light (0.4–0.7 μm), which explains why surfaces with a low albedo appear dark (e.g., trees absorb most radiation), whereas surfaces with a high albedo appear bright (e.g., snow reflects most radiation).
[src:artificialization/albedo] Ice–albedo feedback is a positive feedback climate process where a change in the area of ice caps, glaciers, and sea ice alters the albedo and surface temperature of a planet.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Ice is very reflective, therefore it reflects far more solar energy back to space than the other types of land area or open water.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Ice–albedo feedback plays an important role in global climate change.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Albedo is an important concept in climate science.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The albedo in visible light ranges from about 0.9 to 0.95 for fresh snow to about 0.04 for charcoal, one of the darkest substances.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Deeply shadowed cavities can achieve an effective albedo approaching the zero of a black body.
[src:artificialization/albedo] When seen from a distance, the ocean surface has a low albedo, as do most forests, whereas desert areas have some of the highest albedos among landforms.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Most land areas are in an albedo range of 0.1 to 0.4.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The average albedo of Earth is about 0.3.
[src:artificialization/albedo] This is far higher than for the ocean primarily because of the contribution of clouds.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Earth's surface albedo is regularly estimated via Earth observation satellite sensors such as NASA's MODIS instruments on board the Terra and Aqua satellites, and the CERES instrument on the Suomi NPP and JPSS.
[src:artificialization/albedo] These calculations are based on the bidirectional reflectance distribution function (BRDF), which describes how the reflectance of a given surface depends on the view angle of the observer and the solar angle.
[src:artificialization/albedo] BDRF can facilitate translations of observations of reflectance into albedo.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Earth's average surface temperature due to its albedo and the greenhouse effect is currently about 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:artificialization/albedo] If Earth were frozen entirely (and hence be more reflective), the average temperature of the planet would drop below −40 °C (−40 °F).
[src:artificialization/albedo] If only the continental land masses became covered by glaciers, the mean temperature of the planet would drop to about 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:artificialization/albedo] In contrast, if the entire Earth was covered by water – a so-called ocean planet – the average temperature on the planet would rise to almost 27 °C (81 °F).
[src:artificialization/albedo] In 2021, scientists reported that Earth dimmed by ~0.5% over two decades (1998–2017) as measured by earthshine using modern photometric techniques.
[src:artificialization/albedo] This may have both been co-caused by climate change as well as a substantial increase in global warming.
[src:artificialization/albedo] However, the link to climate change has not been explored to date and it is unclear whether or not this represents an ongoing trend.
[src:artificialization/albedo] This formula is important because it allows the albedo to be calculated for any given illumination conditions from a knowledge of the intrinsic properties of the surface.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Human activities (e.g., deforestation, farming, and urbanization) change the albedo of various areas around the globe.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Human impacts to "the physical properties of the land surface can perturb the climate by altering the Earth's radiative energy balance" even on a small scale or when undetected by satellites.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Urbanization generally decreases albedo (commonly being 0.01–0.02 lower than adjacent croplands), which contributes to global warming.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Deliberately increasing albedo in urban areas can mitigate the urban heat island effect.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Intentionally enhancing the albedo of the Earth's surface, along with its daytime thermal emittance, has been proposed as a solar radiation management strategy to mitigate energy crises and global warming known as passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC).
[src:artificialization/albedo] Efforts toward widespread implementation of PDRCs may focus on maximizing the albedo of surfaces from very low to high values, so long as a thermal emittance of at least 90% can be achieved.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The tens of thousands of hectares of greenhouses in Almería, Spain form a large expanse of whitened plastic roofs.
[src:artificialization/albedo] A 2008 study found that this anthropogenic change lowered the local surface area temperature of the high-albedo area, although changes were localized.
[src:artificialization/albedo] A follow-up study found that "CO2-eq. emissions associated to changes in surface albedo are a consequence of land transformation" and can reduce surface temperature increases associated with climate change.
[src:artificialization/albedo] However, albedo and illumination both vary by latitude.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Albedo is highest near the poles and lowest in the subtropics, with a local maximum in the tropics.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Tropical and sub-tropical rainforest areas have low albedo, and are much hotter than their temperate forest counterparts, which have lower insolation.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Because insolation plays such a big role in the heating and cooling effects of albedo, high insolation areas like the tropics will tend to show a more pronounced fluctuation in local temperature when local albedo changes.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Arctic regions notably release more heat back into space than what they absorb, effectively cooling the Earth.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Since arctic ice and snow have been melting at higher rates due to higher temperatures, creating regions in the arctic that are notably darker (being water or ground which is darker color), there is concern because less heat is reflected back into space.
[src:artificialization/albedo] This feedback loop results in a reduced albedo effect.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Albedo affects climate by determining how much radiation a planet absorbs.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The uneven heating of Earth from albedo variations between land, ice, or ocean surfaces can drive weather.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The response of the climate system to an initial forcing is modified by feedbacks: increased by "self-reinforcing" or "positive" feedbacks and reduced by "balancing" or "negative" feedbacks.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The main reinforcing feedbacks are the water-vapour feedback, the ice–albedo feedback, and the net effect of clouds.
[src:artificialization/albedo] When an area's albedo changes due to snowfall, a snow–temperature feedback results.
[src:artificialization/albedo] A layer of snowfall increases local albedo, reflecting away sunlight, leading to local cooling.
[src:artificialization/albedo] In principle, if no outside temperature change affects this area (e.g., a warm air mass), the raised albedo and lower temperature would maintain the current snow and invite further snowfall, deepening the snow–temperature feedback.
[src:artificialization/albedo] However, because local weather is dynamic due to the change of seasons, eventually warm air masses and a more direct angle of sunlight (higher insolation) cause melting.
[src:artificialization/albedo] When the melted area reveals surfaces with lower albedo, such as grass, soil, or ocean, the effect is reversed: the darkening surface lowers albedo, increasing local temperatures, which induces more melting and thus reducing the albedo further, resulting in still more heating.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Snow albedo is highly variable, ranging from as high as 0.9 for freshly fallen snow, to about 0.4 for melting snow, and as low as 0.2 for dirty snow.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Over Antarctica, snow albedo averages a little more than 0.8.
[src:artificialization/albedo] If a marginally snow-covered area warms, snow tends to melt, lowering the albedo, and hence leading to more snowmelt because more radiation is being absorbed by the snowpack (referred to as the ice–albedo positive feedback).
[src:artificialization/albedo] In Switzerland, the citizens have been protecting their glaciers with large white tarpaulins to slow down the ice melt.
[src:artificialization/albedo] These large white sheets are helping to reject the rays from the sun and defecting the heat.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Although this method is very expensive, it has been shown to work, reducing snow and ice melt by 60%.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Just as fresh snow has a higher albedo than does dirty snow, the albedo of snow-covered sea ice is far higher than that of sea water.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Sea water absorbs more solar radiation than would the same surface covered with reflective snow.
[src:artificialization/albedo] When sea ice melts, either due to a rise in sea temperature or in response to increased solar radiation from above, the snow-covered surface is reduced, and more surface of sea water is exposed, so the rate of energy absorption increases.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The extra absorbed energy heats the sea water, which in turn increases the rate at which sea ice melts.
[src:artificialization/albedo] As with the preceding example of snowmelt, the process of melting of sea ice is thus another example of a positive feedback.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Both positive feedback loops have long been recognized as important for global warming.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Cryoconite, powdery windblown dust containing soot, sometimes reduces albedo on glaciers and ice sheets.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The dynamical nature of albedo in response to positive feedback, together with the effects of small errors in the measurement of albedo, can lead to large errors in energy estimates.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Because of this, in order to reduce the error of energy estimates, it is important to measure the albedo of snow-covered areas through remote sensing techniques rather than applying a single value for albedo over broad regions.
[src:artificialization/albedo] In sunlight, dark clothes absorb more heat and light-coloured clothes reflect it better, thus allowing some control over body temperature by exploiting the albedo effect of the colour of external clothing.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Albedo can affect the electrical energy output of solar photovoltaic devices.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Research showed impacts of over 10% for vertically (90°) mounted systems, but such effects were substantially lower for systems with lower surface tilts.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Spectral albedo strongly affects the performance of bifacial solar cells where rear surface performance gains of over 20% have been observed for c-Si cells installed above healthy vegetation.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Forests generally have a low albedo because the majority of the ultraviolet and visible spectrum is absorbed through photosynthesis.
[src:artificialization/albedo] For this reason, the greater heat absorption by trees could offset some of the carbon benefits of afforestation (or offset the negative climate impacts of deforestation).
[src:artificialization/albedo] In other words: The climate change mitigation effect of carbon sequestration by forests is partially counterbalanced in that reforestation can decrease the reflection of sunlight (albedo).
[src:artificialization/albedo] In the case of evergreen forests with seasonal snow cover, albedo reduction may be significant enough for deforestation to cause a net cooling effect.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Trees also impact climate in extremely complicated ways through evapotranspiration.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The water vapor causes cooling on the land surface, causes heating where it condenses, acts as strong greenhouse gas, and can increase albedo when it condenses into clouds.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Scientists generally treat evapotranspiration as a net cooling impact, and the net climate impact of albedo and evapotranspiration changes from deforestation depends greatly on local climate.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Mid-to-high-latitude forests have a much lower albedo during snow seasons than flat ground, thus contributing to warming.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Modeling that compares the effects of albedo differences between forests and grasslands suggests that expanding the land area of forests in temperate zones offers only a temporary mitigation benefit.
[src:artificialization/albedo] In seasonally snow-covered zones, winter albedos of treeless areas are 10% to 50% higher than nearby forested areas because snow does not cover the trees as readily.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Deciduous trees have an albedo value of about 0.15 to 0.18 whereas coniferous trees have a value of about 0.09 to 0.15.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Variation in summer albedo across both forest types is associated with maximum rates of photosynthesis because plants with high growth capacity display a greater fraction of their foliage for direct interception of incoming radiation in the upper canopy.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The result is that wavelengths of light not used in photosynthesis are more likely to be reflected back to space rather than being absorbed by other surfaces lower in the canopy.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Studies by the Hadley Centre have investigated the relative (generally warming) effect of albedo change and (cooling) effect of carbon sequestration on planting forests.
[src:artificialization/albedo] They found that new forests in tropical and midlatitude areas tended to cool; new forests in high latitudes (e.g., Siberia) were neutral or perhaps warming.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Research in 2023, drawing from 176 flux stations globally, revealed a climate trade-off: increased carbon uptake from afforestation results in reduced albedo.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Initially, this reduction may lead to moderate global warming over a span of approximately 20 years, but it is expected to transition into significant cooling thereafter.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Water reflects light very differently from typical terrestrial materials.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The reflectivity of a water surface is calculated using the Fresnel equations.
[src:artificialization/albedo] At the scale of the wavelength of light even wavy water is always smooth so the light is reflected in a locally specular manner (not diffusely).
[src:artificialization/albedo] The glint of light off water is a commonplace effect of this.
[src:artificialization/albedo] At small angles of incident light, waviness results in reduced reflectivity because of the steepness of the reflectivity-vs.-incident-angle curve and a locally increased average incident angle.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Although the reflectivity of water is very low at low and medium angles of incident light, it becomes very high at high angles of incident light such as those that occur on the illuminated side of Earth near the terminator (early morning, late afternoon, and near the poles).
[src:artificialization/albedo] However, as mentioned above, waviness causes an appreciable reduction.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Because light specularly reflected from water does not usually reach the viewer, water is usually considered to have a very low albedo in spite of its high reflectivity at high angles of incident light.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Note that white caps on waves look white (and have high albedo) because the water is foamed up, so there are many superimposed bubble surfaces which reflect, adding up their reflectivities.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Fresh 'black' ice exhibits Fresnel reflection.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Snow on top of this sea ice increases the albedo to 0.9.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Cloud albedo has substantial influence over atmospheric temperatures.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Different types of clouds exhibit different reflectivity, theoretically ranging in albedo from a minimum of near 0 to a maximum approaching 0.8.
[src:artificialization/albedo] "On any given day, about half of Earth is covered by clouds, which reflect more sunlight than land and water.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Albedo and climate in some areas are affected by artificial clouds, such as those created by the contrails of heavy commercial airliner traffic.
[src:artificialization/albedo] A study following the burning of the Kuwaiti oil fields during Iraqi occupation showed that temperatures under the burning oil fires were as much as 10 °C (18 °F) colder than temperatures several miles away under clear skies.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Aerosols (very fine particles/droplets in the atmosphere) have both direct and indirect effects on Earth's radiative balance.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The direct (albedo) effect is generally to cool the planet; the indirect effect (the particles act as cloud condensation nuclei and thereby change cloud properties) is less certain.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Another albedo-related effect on the climate is from black carbon particles.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The size of this effect is difficult to quantify: the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that the global mean radiative forcing for black carbon aerosols from fossil fuels is +0.2 W m−2, with a range +0.1 to +0.4 W m−2.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Black carbon is a bigger cause of the melting of the polar ice cap in the Arctic than carbon dioxide due to its effect on the albedo.
[src:artificialization/albedo] In astronomy, the term **albedo** can be defined in several different ways, depending upon the application and the wavelength of electromagnetic radiation involved.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The albedos of planets, satellites and minor planets such as asteroids can be used to infer much about their properties.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The study of albedos, their dependence on wavelength, lighting angle ("phase angle"), and variation in time composes a major part of the astronomical field of photometry.
[src:artificialization/albedo] For small and far objects that cannot be resolved by telescopes, much of what we know comes from the study of their albedos.
[src:artificialization/albedo] For example, the absolute albedo can indicate the surface ice content of outer Solar System objects, the variation of albedo with phase angle gives information about regolith properties, whereas unusually high radar albedo is indicative of high metal content in asteroids.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Enceladus, a moon of Saturn, has one of the highest known optical albedos of any body in the Solar System, with an albedo of 0.99.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Another notable high-albedo body is Eris, with an albedo of 0.96.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Many small objects in the outer Solar System and asteroid belt have low albedos down to about 0.05.
[src:artificialization/albedo] A typical comet nucleus has an albedo of 0.04.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Such a dark surface is thought to be indicative of a primitive and heavily space weathered surface containing some organic compounds.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The overall albedo of the Moon is measured to be around 0.14, but it is strongly directional and non-Lambertian, displaying also a strong opposition effect.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Although such reflectance properties are different from those of any terrestrial terrains, they are typical of the regolith surfaces of airless Solar System bodies.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Two common optical albedos that are used in astronomy are the (V-band) geometric albedo (measuring brightness when illumination comes from directly behind the observer) and the Bond albedo (measuring total proportion of electromagnetic energy reflected).
[src:artificialization/albedo] Their values can differ significantly, which is a common source of confusion.
[src:artificialization/albedo] In detailed studies, the directional reflectance properties of astronomical bodies are often expressed in terms of the five Hapke parameters which semi-empirically describe the variation of albedo with phase angle, including a characterization of the opposition effect of regolith surfaces.
[src:artificialization/albedo] One of these five parameters is yet another type of albedo called the single-scattering albedo.
[src:artificialization/albedo] It is used to define scattering of electromagnetic waves on small particles.
[src:artificialization/albedo] It depends on properties of the material (refractive index), the size of the particle, and the wavelength of the incoming radiation.
[src:artificialization/albedo] An important relationship between an object's astronomical (geometric) albedo, absolute magnitude and diameter is given by: $A=\left({\frac {1329\times 10^{-H/5}}{D}}\right)^{2},$ where A is the astronomical albedo, D is the diameter in kilometers, and H is the absolute magnitude.
[src:artificialization/albedo] In planetary radar astronomy, a microwave (or radar) pulse is transmitted toward a planetary target (e.g.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Moon, asteroid, etc.) and the echo from the target is measured.
[src:artificialization/albedo] In most instances, the transmitted pulse is circularly polarized and the received pulse is measured in the same sense of polarization as the transmitted pulse (SC) and the opposite sense (OC).
[src:artificialization/albedo] The echo power is measured in terms of radar cross-section, ${\sigma }_{OC}$ , ${\sigma }_{SC}$ , or ${\sigma }_{T}$ (total power, SC + OC) and is equal to the cross-sectional area of a metallic sphere (perfect reflector) at the same distance as the target that would return the same echo power.
[src:artificialization/albedo] Those components of the received echo that return from first-surface reflections (as from a smooth or mirror-like surface) are dominated by the OC component as there is a reversal in polarization upon reflection.
[src:artificialization/albedo] If the surface is rough at the wavelength scale or there is significant penetration into the regolith, there will be a significant SC component in the echo caused by multiple scattering.
[src:artificialization/albedo] where the denominator is the effective cross-sectional area of the target object with mean radius, r .
[src:artificialization/albedo] A smooth metallic sphere would have ${\hat {\sigma }}_{\text{OC}}=1$ .
[src:artificialization/albedo] The values reported for the Moon, Mercury, Mars, Venus, and Comet P/2005 JQ5 are derived from the total (OC+SC) radar albedo reported in those references.
[src:artificialization/albedo] The term albedo was introduced into optics by Johann Heinrich Lambert in his 1760 work *Photometria*.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] In geography and ecology, **anthropization** is the conversion of open spaces, landscapes, and natural environments by human action.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Anthropic erosion is the process of human action degrading terrain and soil.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] An area may be classified as anthropized even though it looks natural, such as grasslands that have been deforested by humans.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] It can be difficult to determine how much a site has been anthropized in the case of urbanization because one must be able to estimate the state of the landscape before significant human action.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] The earliest known stages of anthropization can be found as early as the Neolithic era and the basic farmland created in that time.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] With the continually-growing population of humans, the land that the Earth provides has been appropriated over the years.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] The ecological footprint created by anthropization is continually growing despite efficiency and technique improvements made in anthropization..
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Whether anthropized or not, all land seldom a few locations has been claimed.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Outside of the largely inhospitable Arctic and Antarctic circles and large portions of other uninhabitable landscapes, much of the globe has been used or altered in some direct way by humans.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Land has been appropriated for many different reasons, but ultimately the outcome is typically a short-term benefit for humans.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] An area is anthropized is some way to make land available for housing, to harvest the resources, to create space for some anthropological reason, or many other possibilities.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] The root of many early forms of civilization, agriculture has been a primary reason for anthropization.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] To cultivate food or breed animals, humans must alter land—till soil or build structures—to facilitate agriculture.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] This can lead to soil erosion and pollution (pesticides, greenhouse gas emissions, etc.), and subsequently habitat fragmentation and overall an increased ecological footprint.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Agriculture and industry often overlap, and industry produces many of these effects too.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Especially with approximately 7.5 Billion humans inhabiting the Earth, this typically aligns with an increase in residences worldwide.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Over the years, humans have built on land to meet their needs and wants.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] These actions range from small villages to massive factories, water parks, and apartments.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Urbanization and development of human residences can significantly affect the environment.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Not only does the physical space of buildings fragment habitats and possibly endanger species, but it fundamentally alters the habitat for any other living being.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] For some species, this effect can be inconsequential, but for many this can have a dramatic impact.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] The biosphere is very much interconnected, and this means that if one organism is affected, then as a result the other organisms within this ecosystem and food chain are also affected.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] As well, within the last century, any urbanized area requires roads for transportation.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] This transportation is a continued source of pollution, and the roads can be a source of soil erosion.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] To support humans, industrial buildings and processes are apparently essential.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Urban development and agriculture require that people produce, refined, or construct many things.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Key to this is that factories require that people gather the materials they need to create a product.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] The wide range of products in this anthropological age use a plethora of substances that must be harvested or produced.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Many of these materials are non-renewable (e.g., fossil fuel, metal ores, etc.) and the harvest of these results in relatively permanent anthropization.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] For resources that depend on in high quantity, this can also mean temporary depletion or damage to the source of the resource (e.g., depletion or pollution of fresh water reserves, improper or inefficient silviculture, etc.).
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Even sustainable or renewable industrial anthropization still affects the environment.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] While the resource in question may not be in jeopardy, the harvest and processing can still change and damage the environment.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Anthropization can also be a result of scientific endeavours.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] This can manifest as construction of structures to aid in scientific discovery and observation.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] This can range from structures such as observatories, or on the opposite scale the Large Hadron Collider.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] These and many other things are built and used to enhance knowledge of sciences.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] They do however require space and energy.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] To power the ever-growing human race, energy is needed.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Power-harvesting structures are built to harness energy, such as dams, windmills, and nuclear reactors.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] These sources of energy ultimately fuel the rest of anthropological activity and are essential in this way.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] However many of these methods have consequences.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] With dams, construction aside, they can cause flooding, habitat fragmentation, and other effects.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] With nuclear reactors, they have a lasting effect in that typically a lifespan of one of these is around 50 years and afterwards the nuclear waste must be dealt with, and the structure itself must be shut down and cannot be used further.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] To safely dispose of this even low-level waste can take hundreds of years, ranging upwards with increased radioactivity.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] To produce and as a result of this production of energy, it requires a lot of anthropized land.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Changes in population directly effect anthropological impact—but changes in technology and knowledge have greatly changed anthropization throughout the Holocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] The tools and methods that humans use to anthropize have changed drastically.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] For examples, the great pyramids in Egypt were not constructed by some large machine, but instead by thousands of humans.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] They were still able to build massive monuments, but the efficiency of their efforts and environmental damage was very different from what would be possible today.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] This shows that the environmental effect of modern anthropization is generally greater, not just because of the increase in population.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] Pollution and loss of biodiversity in Egypt was largely natural, not man-made, and anthropization existed on a much lower level.
[src:artificialization/anthropization] As the human population of Earth increase, this anthropization will continue to evolve.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The term has been used in sophisticated research relating to Earth's water and salt, geology, geomorphology, landscape, limnology, hydrology, ecosystems and climate.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The effects of human activities on Earth can be seen, for example, in regards to biodiversity loss, and climate change.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Various start dates for the Anthropocene have been proposed, ranging from the beginning of the Neolithic Revolution (12,000–15,000 years ago), to as recently as the 1960s.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Stoermer is credited with first coining and using the term *anthropocene* informally in the 1980s; Paul J.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Crutzen re-invented and popularized the term.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The Anthropocene Working Group (AWG) of the Subcommission on Quaternary Stratigraphy (SQS) of the ICS voted in 2016 to proceed towards a formal golden spike (GSSP) proposal to define an Anthropocene epoch in the geologic time scale.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Later that year, the group presented the proposal to the International Geological Congress.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In 2019, the AWG voted in favour of submitting a formal proposal to the ICS by 2021.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The proposal located potential stratigraphic markers to the mid-20th century.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This time period coincides with the start of the Great Acceleration, a post-World War II time period during which global population growth, economic growth, pollution and exploitation of natural resources have all increased at a dramatic rate.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The Atomic Age also started around the mid-20th century, when the risks of nuclear wars, nuclear terrorism, and nuclear accidents increased.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Twelve candidate sites were selected for the GSSP; the sediments of Crawford Lake (Halton Region), Canada were finally proposed, in 2023, to mark the lower boundary of the Anthropocene, starting with the Crawfordian stage/age in 1950.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In 2024, after 15 years of deliberation, the Anthropocene Epoch proposal of the AWG was voted down by a wide margin by the SQS, owing largely to its shallow sedimentary record and extremely recent proposed start date.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The ICS and the IUGS later formally confirmed, by a near unanimous vote, the rejection of the AWG's Anthropocene Epoch proposal for inclusion in the Geologic Time Scale.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] As early as 1873, the Italian geologist Antonio Stoppani acknowledged the increasing power and effect of humanity on the Earth's systems and referred to an 'anthropozoic era'.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] From 1877 onward, the term 'Psychozoic' was used by geologists such as Joseph LeConte and Johannes Herman Frederik Umbgrove.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] An early concept for the Anthropocene was the Noosphere by Vladimir Vernadsky, who in 1938 wrote of "scientific thought as a geological force".
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Scientists in the Soviet Union appear to have used the term *Anthropocene* as early as the 1960s to refer to the Quaternary, the most recent geological period.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Stoermer subsequently used *Anthropocene* with a different sense in the 1980s and the term was widely popularised in 2000 by atmospheric chemist Paul J.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Crutzen, who regarded the influence of human behavior on Earth's atmosphere in recent centuries as so significant as to constitute a new geological epoch.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The term *Anthropocene* is informally used in scientific contexts.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The Geological Society of America entitled its 2011 annual meeting: *Archean to Anthropocene: The past is the key to the future*.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The new epoch has no agreed start-date, but one proposal, based on atmospheric evidence, is to fix the start with the Industrial Revolution c.1780, with the invention of the steam engine.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Other scientists link the new term to earlier events, such as the rise of agriculture and the Neolithic Revolution (around 12,000 years BP).
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Evidence of relative human impact – such as the growing human influence on land use, ecosystems, biodiversity, and species extinction – is substantial; scientists think that human impact has significantly changed (or halted) the growth of biodiversity.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In 2008, the Stratigraphy Commission of the Geological Society of London considered a proposal to make the Anthropocene a formal unit of geological epoch divisions.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] A majority of the commission decided the proposal had merit and should be examined further.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Independent working groups of scientists from various geological societies began to determine whether the Anthropocene will be formally accepted into the Geological Time Scale.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In January 2015, 26 of the 38 members of the International Anthropocene Working Group published a paper suggesting the Trinity test on 16 July 1945 as the starting point of the proposed new epoch.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] However, a significant minority supported one of several alternative dates.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] A March 2015 report suggested either 1610 or 1964 as the beginning of the Anthropocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Other scholars pointed to the diachronous character of the physical strata of the Anthropocene, arguing that onset and impact are spread out over time, not reducible to a single instant or date of start.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] A January 2016 report on the climatic, biological, and geochemical signatures of human activity in sediments and ice cores suggested the era since the mid-20th century should be recognised as a geological epoch distinct from the Holocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The Anthropocene Working Group met in April 2016 to consolidate evidence supporting the argument for the *Anthropocene* as a true geologic epoch.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Evidence was evaluated and the group voted to recommend *Anthropocene* as the new geological epoch in August 2016.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In April 2019, the Anthropocene Working Group (AWG) announced that they would vote on a formal proposal to the International Commission on Stratigraphy, to continue the process started at the 2016 meeting.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In May 2019, 29 members of the 34 person AWG panel voted in favour of an official proposal to be made by 2021.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The AWG also voted with 29 votes in favour of a starting date in the mid 20th century.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Ten candidate sites for a Global boundary Stratotype Section and Point have been identified, one of which will be chosen to be included in the final proposal.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Possible markers include microplastics, heavy metals, or radioactive nuclei left by tests from thermonuclear weapons.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In November 2021, an alternative proposal that the Anthropocene is a geological event, not an epoch, was published and later expanded in 2022.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This challenged the assumption underlying the case for the Anthropocene epoch – the idea that it is possible to accurately assign a precise date of start to highly diachronous processes of human-influenced Earth system change.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The argument indicated that finding a single GSSP would be impractical, given human-induced changes in the Earth system occurred at different periods, in different places, and spread under different rates.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The authors are members of the AWG who had voted against the official proposal of a starting date in the mid-20th century, and sought to reconcile some of the previous models (including Ruddiman and Maslin proposals).
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] They cited Crutzen's original concept, arguing that the Anthropocene is much better and more usefully conceived of as an unfolding geological event, like other major transformations in Earth's history such as the Great Oxidation Event.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In July 2023, the AWG chose Crawford Lake in Ontario, Canada as a site representing the beginning of the proposed new epoch.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Had it been approved, the official declaration of the new Anthropocene epoch would have taken place in August 2024, and its first age may have been named **Crawfordian** after the lake.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In March 2024, an internal vote was held by the IUGS: After nearly 15 years of debate, the proposal to ratify the Anthropocene had been defeated by a 12-to-4 margin, with 2 abstentions.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] These results were not out of a dismissal of human impact on the planet, but rather an inability to constrain the Anthropocene in a geological context.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This is because the widely-adopted 1950 start date was found to be prone to recency bias.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] It also overshadowed earlier examples of human impacts, many of which happened in different parts of the world at different times.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Although the proposal could be raised again, this would require the entire process of debate to start from the beginning.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The results of the vote were officially confirmed by the IUGS and upheld as definitive later that month.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Crutzen proposed the Industrial Revolution as the start of Anthropocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Lovelock proposes that the Anthropocene began with the first application of the Newcomen steam engine in 1712.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change takes the pre-industrial era (chosen as the year 1750) as the baseline related to changes in long-lived, well mixed greenhouse gases.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Although it is apparent that the Industrial Revolution ushered in an unprecedented global human impact on the planet, much of Earth's landscape already had been profoundly modified by human activities.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The human impact on Earth has grown progressively, with few substantial slowdowns.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] A 2024 scientific perspective paper authored by a group of scientists led by William J.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In May 2019 the twenty-nine members of the Anthropocene Working Group (AWG) proposed a start date for the Epoch in the mid-20th century, as that period saw "a rapidly rising human population accelerated the pace of industrial production, the use of agricultural chemicals and other human activities.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The peak in radionuclides fallout consequential to atomic bomb testing during the 1950s is another possible date for the beginning of the Anthropocene (the detonation of the first atomic bomb in 1945 or the Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty in 1963).
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] On 19 June 2025, Vincent Gauci proposed that Anthropocene began in 1592.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Ice core records had shown a minimum atmospheric methane concentration at that time.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The name *Anthropocene* is a combination of *anthropo-* from the Ancient Greek ἄνθρωπος (*ánthropos*) meaning 'human' and *-cene* from καινός (*kainós*) meaning 'new' or 'recent'.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The human impact on biodiversity forms one of the primary attributes of the Anthropocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Humankind has entered what is sometimes called the Earth's sixth major extinction.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Most experts agree that human activities have accelerated the rate of species extinction.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The exact rate remains controversial – perhaps 100 to 1000 times the normal background rate of extinction.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Anthropogenic extinctions started as humans migrated out of Africa over 60,000 years ago.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Increases in global rates of extinction have been elevated above background rates since at least 1500, and appear to have accelerated in the 19th century and further since.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Rapid economic growth is considered a primary driver of the contemporary displacement and eradication of other species.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Biodiversity loss happens when species disappear completely from Earth (extinction) or when there is a decrease or disappearance of species in a specific area.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Biodiversity loss means that there is a reduction in biological diversity in a given area.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The decrease can be temporary or permanent.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] It is temporary if the damage that led to the loss is reversible in time, for example through ecological restoration.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] If this is not possible, then the decrease is permanent.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The cause of most of the biodiversity loss is, generally speaking, human activities that push the planetary boundaries too far.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] These activities include habitat destruction (for example deforestation) and land use intensification (for example monoculture farming).
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Further problem areas are air and water pollution (including nutrient pollution), over-exploitation, invasive species and climate change.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Many scientists, along with the *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services*, say that the main reason for biodiversity loss is a growing human population because this leads to human overpopulation and excessive consumption.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Others disagree, saying that loss of habitat is caused mainly by "the growth of commodities for export" and that population has very little to do with overall consumption.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] More important are wealth disparities between and within countries.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In any case, all contemporary biodiversity loss has been attributed to human activities.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Climate change is another threat to global biodiversity.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] For example, coral reefs—which are biodiversity hotspots—will be lost by the year 2100 if global warming continues at the current rate.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Additionally, the change of temperatures are likely to increase fire activity driving events such as forest fires.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Still, it is the general habitat destruction (often for expansion of agriculture), not climate change, that is currently the bigger driver of biodiversity loss.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Invasive species and other disturbances have become more common in forests in the last several decades.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] These tend to be directly or indirectly connected to climate change and can cause a deterioration of forest ecosystems.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Studies of urban evolution give an indication of how species may respond to stressors such as temperature change and toxicity.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Species display varying abilities to respond to altered environments through both phenotypic plasticity and genetic evolution.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Researchers have documented the movement of many species into regions formerly too cold for them, often at rates faster than initially expected.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Permanent changes in the distribution of organisms from human influence will become identifiable in the geologic record.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This has occurred in part as a result of changing climate, but also in response to farming and fishing, and to the accidental introduction of non-native species to new areas through global travel.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The ecosystem of the entire Black Sea may have changed during the last 2000 years as a result of nutrient and silica input from eroding deforested lands along the Danube River.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Researchers have found that the growth of the human population and expansion of human activity has resulted in many species of animals that are normally active during the day, such as elephants, tigers and boars, becoming nocturnal to avoid contact with humans, who are largely diurnal.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] One geological symptom resulting from human activity is increasing atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) content.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This signal in the Earth's climate system is especially significant because it is occurring much faster, and to a greater extent, than previously.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Most of this increase is due to the combustion of fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and gas.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Effects of climate change are well documented and growing for Earth's natural environment and human societies.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Changes to the climate system include an overall warming trend, changes to precipitation patterns, and more extreme weather.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] As the climate changes it impacts the natural environment with effects such as more intense forest fires, thawing permafrost, and desertification.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] These changes impact ecosystems and societies, and can become irreversible once tipping points are crossed.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Climate activists are engaged in a range of activities around the world that seek to ameliorate these issues or prevent them from happening.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The effects of climate change vary in timing and location.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Up until now the Arctic has warmed faster than most other regions due to climate change feedbacks.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Surface air temperatures over land have also increased at about twice the rate they do over the ocean, causing intense heat waves.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] These temperatures would stabilize if greenhouse gas emissions were brought under control.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Ice sheets and oceans absorb the vast majority of excess heat in the atmosphere, delaying effects there but causing them to accelerate and then continue after surface temperatures stabilize.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Sea level rise is a particular long term concern as a result.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The effects of ocean warming also include marine heatwaves, ocean stratification, deoxygenation, and changes to ocean currents.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The ocean is also acidifying as it absorbs carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Changes in drainage patterns traceable to human activity will persist over geologic time in large parts of the continents where the geologic regime is erosional.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This involves, for example, the paths of roads and highways defined by their grading and drainage control.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Direct changes to the form of the Earth's surface by human activities (quarrying and landscaping, for example) also record human impacts.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] It has been suggested that the deposition of calthemite formations exemplify a natural process which has not previously occurred prior to the human modification of the Earth's surface, and which therefore represents a unique process of the Anthropocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Calthemite is a secondary deposit, derived from concrete, lime, mortar or other calcareous material *outside the cave environment*.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Calthemites grow on or under man-made structures (including mines and tunnels) and mimic the shapes and forms of cave speleothems, such as stalactites, stalagmites, flowstone *etc*.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Human activities, including deforestation and road construction, are believed to have elevated average total sediment fluxes across the Earth's surface.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] However, construction of dams on many rivers around the world means the rates of sediment deposition in any given place do not always appear to increase in the Anthropocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] For instance, many river deltas around the world are actually currently starved of sediment by such dams, and are subsiding and failing to keep up with sea level rise, rather than growing.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Increases in erosion due to farming and other operations will be reflected by changes in sediment composition and increases in deposition rates elsewhere.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In land areas with a depositional regime, engineered structures will tend to be buried and preserved, along with litter and debris.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Litter and debris thrown from boats or carried by rivers and creeks will accumulate in the marine environment, particularly in coastal areas, but also in mid-ocean garbage patches.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Such human-created artifacts preserved in stratigraphy are known as *technofossils*.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Changes in biodiversity will also be reflected in the fossil record, as will species introductions.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Hence, landfills are important resources to find "technofossils".
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In terms of trace elements, there are a range of distinct signatures left by modern societies.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] For example, in the Upper Fremont Glacier in Wyoming, there is a layer of chlorine present in ice cores from 1960's atomic weapon testing programs, as well as a layer of mercury associated with coal plants in the 1980s.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] From the late 1940s, nuclear tests have led to local nuclear fallout and severe contamination of test sites both on land and in the surrounding marine environment.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Some of the radionuclides that were released during the tests are 137Cs, 90Sr, 239Pu, 240Pu, 241Am, and 131I.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] These have been found to have had significant impact on the environment and on human beings.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In particular, 137Cs and 90Sr have been found to have been released into the marine environment and led to bioaccumulation over a period through food chain cycles.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The carbon isotope 14C, commonly released during nuclear tests, has also been found to be integrated into the atmospheric CO2, and infiltrating the biosphere, through ocean-atmosphere gas exchange.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Increase in thyroid cancer rates around the world is also surmised to be correlated with increasing proportions of the 131I radionuclide.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The highest global concentration of radionuclides was estimated to have been in 1965, one of the dates which has been proposed as a possible benchmark for the start of the formally defined Anthropocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Human burning of fossil fuels has also left distinctly elevated concentrations of black carbon, inorganic ash, and spherical carbonaceous particles in recent sediments across the world.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Concentrations of these components increases markedly and almost simultaneously around the world beginning around 1950.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] A marker that accounts for a substantial global impact of humans on the total environment, comparable in scale to those associated with significant perturbations of the geological past, is needed in place of minor changes in atmosphere composition.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] A range of markers characterizing the period have been identified, such as silicone or aluminium, but most prominently plastic, with plastic, reminiscent of archaeological ages like the Iron Age, marking an archaeological plastic age or the anthropocene even as a geological **plastic epoch**.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] A useful candidate for holding markers in the geologic time record is the pedosphere.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Soils retain information about their climatic and geochemical history with features lasting for centuries or millennia.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Human activity is now firmly established as the sixth factor of soil formation.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Human activity also affects pedogenesis indirectly by drift of eroded materials or pollutants.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Anthropogenic soils are those markedly affected by human activities, such as repeated ploughing, the addition of fertilisers, contamination, sealing, or enrichment with artefacts (in the World Reference Base for Soil Resources they are classified as Anthrosols and Technosols).
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] An example from archaeology would be dark earth phenomena when long-term human habitation enriches the soil with black carbon.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Anthropogenic soils are recalcitrant repositories of artefacts and properties that testify to the dominance of the human impact, and hence appear to be reliable markers for the Anthropocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Some anthropogenic soils may be viewed as the 'golden spikes' of geologists (Global Boundary Stratotype Section and Point), which are locations where there are strata successions with clear evidences of a worldwide event, including the appearance of distinctive fossils.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Drilling for fossil fuels has also created holes and tubes which are expected to be detectable for millions of years.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] An October 2020 study coordinated by University of Colorado at Boulder found that distinct physical, chemical and biological changes to Earth's rock layers began around the year 1950.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Humans have produced so many millions of tons of plastic each year since the early 1950s that microplastics are "forming a near-ubiquitous and unambiguous marker of Anthropocene".
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The study highlights a strong correlation between global human population size and growth, global productivity and global energy use and that the "extraordinary outburst of consumption and productivity demonstrates how the Earth System has departed from its Holocene state since c.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Although the validity of *Anthropocene* as a scientific term remains disputed, its underlying premise, i.e., that humans have become a geological force, or rather, the dominant force shaping the Earth's climate, has found traction among academics and the public.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In an opinion piece for *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*, Rodolfo Dirzo, Gerardo Ceballos, and Paul R.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Ehrlich write that the term is "increasingly penetrating the lexicon of not only the academic socio-sphere, but also society more generally", and is now included as an entry in the Oxford English Dictionary.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The University of Cambridge, as another example, offers a degree in Anthropocene Studies.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In the public sphere, the term *Anthropocene* has become increasingly ubiquitous in activist, pundit, and political discourses.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Other scholars appreciate the way in which the term *Anthropocene* recognizes humanity as a geological force, but take issue with the indiscriminate way in which it does.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Not all humans are equally responsible for the climate crisis.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] To that end, scholars such as the feminist theorist Donna Haraway and sociologist Jason Moore, have suggested naming the Epoch instead as the *Capitalocene*.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Such implies capitalism as the fundamental reason for the ecological crisis, rather than just humans in general.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] However, according to philosopher Steven Best, humans have created "hierarchical and growth-addicted societies" and have demonstrated "ecocidal proclivities" long before the emergence of capitalism.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Hartigan, Bould, and Haraway all critique what *Anthropocene* does as a term; however, Hartigan and Bould differ from Haraway in that they criticize the utility or validity of a geological framing of the climate crisis, whereas Haraway embraces it.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In addition to "Capitalocene," other terms have also been proposed by scholars to trace the roots of the Epoch to causes other than the human species broadly.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Janae Davis, for example, has suggested the "Plantationocene" as a more appropriate term to call attention to the role that plantation agriculture has played in the formation of the Epoch, alongside Kathryn Yusoff's argument that racism as a whole is foundational to the Epoch.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Other critiques of *Anthropocene* have focused on the genealogy of the concept.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] To that end, Todd makes the case that the concept of *Anthropocene* must be indigenized and decolonized if it is to become a vehicle of justice as opposed to white thought and domination.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Eco-philosopher David Abram, in a book chapter titled 'Interbreathing in the Humilocene', has proposed adoption of the term 'Humilocene' (the Epoch of Humility), which emphasizes an ethical imperative and ecocultural direction that human societies should take.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The term plays with the etymological roots of the term 'human', thus connecting it back with terms such as humility, humus (the soil), and even a corrective sense of humiliation that some human societies should feel given their collective destructive impact on the earth.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] William Ruddiman has argued that the Anthropocene began approximately 8,000 years ago with the development of farming and sedentary cultures.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] At that point, humans were dispersed across all continents except Antarctica, and the Neolithic Revolution was ongoing.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] During this period, humans developed agriculture and animal husbandry to supplement or replace hunter-gatherer subsistence.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Such innovations were followed by a wave of extinctions, beginning with large mammals and terrestrial birds.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This wave was driven by both the direct activity of humans (e.g. hunting) and the indirect consequences of land-use change for agriculture.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Landscape-scale burning by prehistoric hunter-gathers may have been an additional early source of anthropogenic atmospheric carbon.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Ruddiman also claims that the greenhouse gas emissions in-part responsible for the Anthropocene began 8,000 years ago when ancient farmers cleared forests to grow crops.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Ruddiman's work has been challenged with data from an earlier interglaciation ("Stage 11", approximately 400,000 years ago) which suggests that 16,000 more years must elapse before the current Holocene interglaciation comes to an end, and thus the early anthropogenic hypothesis is invalid.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Also, the argument that "something" is needed to explain the differences in the Holocene is challenged by more recent research showing that all interglacials are different.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] This is due to the newfound globalism that humans participate in, as species traveling across the world to another region was not as easily possible in any point of time in history as it is today.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Curnutt in the year 2000 in *Ecology*, in a short list titled "A Guide to the Homogenocene", which reviewed *Alien species in North America and Hawaii: impacts on natural ecosystems* by George Cox.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Mann, in his acclaimed book *1493: Uncovering the New World Columbus Created*, gives a bird's-eye view of the mechanisms and ongoing implications of the homogenocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The concept of the Anthropocene has also been approached via humanities such as philosophy, literature and art.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In the scholarly world, it has been the subject of increasing attention through special journals, conferences, and disciplinary reports.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] The Anthropocene, its attendant timescale, and ecological implications prompt questions about death and the end of civilisation, memory and archives, the scope and methods of humanistic inquiry, and emotional responses to the "end of nature".
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Some scholars have posited that the realities of the Anthropocene, including "human-induced biodiversity loss, exponential increases in per-capita resource consumption, and global climate change," have made the goal of environmental sustainability largely unattainable and obsolete.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Historians have actively engaged the Anthropocene.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In 2000, the same year that Paul Crutzen coined the term, world historian John McNeill published *Something New Under the Sun*, tracing the rise of human societies' unprecedented impact on the planet in the twentieth century.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] In 2001, historian of science Naomi Oreskes revealed the systematic efforts to undermine trust in climate change science and went on to detail the corporate interests delaying action on the environmental challenge.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Both McNeill and Oreskes became members of the Anthropocene Working Group because of their work correlating human activities and planetary transformation.
[src:artificialization/anthropocene] Bridie Lonie has reflected that the Anthropocene has been a theme for art in New Zealand since the 1970s.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] There are traces of human settlement by prehistoric peoples, especially in the Périgord, but the earliest attested inhabitants in the south-west were the Aquitani, who were not considered Celtic people, but more akin to the Iberians (see Gallia Aquitania).
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Although a number of different languages and dialects were in use in the area during ancient times, it is most likely that the prevailing language of Aquitaine during the late pre-historic to Roman period was an early form of the Basque language.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] This has been demonstrated by various Aquitanian names and words that were recorded by the Romans, and which are currently easily readable as Basque.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Whether this Aquitanian language (Proto-Basque) was a remnant of a Vasconic language group that once extended much farther, or it was generally limited to the Aquitaine/Basque region, is not known.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] One reason the language of Aquitaine is important is that Basque is the last surviving non-Indo-European language in western Europe and it has had some effect on the languages around it, including Spanish and, to a lesser extent, French.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The original Aquitania (named after the inhabitants) at the time of Caesar's conquest of Gaul included the area bounded by the river Garonne, the Pyrenees and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The name may stem from Latin 'aqua', maybe derived from the town "Aquae Augustae", "Aquae Tarbellicae" or just "Aquis" (Dax, Akize in modern Basque) or as a more general geographical feature.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Under Augustus' Roman rule, from 27 BCE the province of Aquitania was further stretched to the north to the river Loire, thus including proper Gaul tribes along with old Aquitani south of the Garonne (cf.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Novempopulania and Gascony) within the same region.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In 392, the Roman imperial provinces were restructured as *Aquitania Prima* (north-east), *Aquitania Secunda* (centre) and *Aquitania Tertia*, better known as *Novempopulania* in the south-west.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Accounts of Aquitania during the Early Middle Ages are imprecise, but there was much unrest.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The Visigoths were called into Gaul as *foederati*, legalizing their status within the Empire.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Eventually they established themselves as the *de facto* rulers in south-west Gaul as central Roman rule collapsed.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Visigoths established their capital in Toulouse, but their tenure on Aquitaine was feeble.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In 507, they were expelled south to Hispania after their defeat in the Battle of Vouillé by the Franks, who became the new rulers in the area to the south of the Loire.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The Roman Aquitania Tertia remained in place as Novempopulania, where a duke was appointed to hold a grip over the Basques (Vascones/Wascones, rendered *Gascons* in English).
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] These dukes were quite detached from central Frankish overlordship, sometimes governing as independent rulers with strong ties to their kinsmen south of the Pyrenees.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] As of 660, the foundations for an independent Aquitaine/Vasconia polity were established by the duke Felix of Aquitaine, a magnate (*potente(m)*) from Toulouse, probably of Gallo-Roman stock.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Despite its nominal submission to the Merovingians, the ethnic make-up of the new Aquitanian realm was not Frankish, but Gallo-Roman north of the Garonne and in main towns and Basque, especially south of the Garonne.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] A united Basque-Aquitanian realm reached its heyday under Odo the Great's rule.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In 721, the Aquitanian duke fended Umayyad troops (*Sarracens*) off at Toulouse, but in 732 (or 733, according to Roger Collins), an Umayyad expedition commanded by Abdul Rahman Al Ghafiqi defeated Odo next to Bordeaux, and went on to loot its way up to Poitiers.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Odo was required to pledge allegiance to the Frankish Charles Martel in exchange for help against the advancing Arab forces.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Basque-Aquitanian self-rule temporarily came to a halt, definitely in 768 after the assassination of Waifer.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In 781, Charlemagne decided to proclaim his son Louis King of Aquitaine within the Carolingian Empire, ruling over a realm comprising the Duchy of Aquitaine and the Duchy of Vasconia.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] He suppressed various Basque (*Gascon*) uprisings, even venturing into the lands of Pamplona past the Pyrenees after ravaging Gascony, with a view to imposing his authority also in the Vasconia to south of Pyrenees.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] According to his biography, he achieved everything he wanted and after staying overnight in Pamplona, on his way back his army was attacked in Roncevaux in 812, but narrowly escaped an engagement at the Pyrenean passes.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Seguin (Sihiminus), count of Bordeaux and Duke of Vasconia, seemed to have attempted a detachment from the Frankish central authority on Charlemagne's death.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The new emperor Louis the Pious reacted by removing him from his capacity, which stirred the Basques into rebellion.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The king in turn sent his troops to the territory, obtaining their submission in two campaigns and killing the duke, while his family crossed the Pyrenees and continued to foment risings against Frankish power.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In 824, the 2nd Battle of Roncevaux took place, in which counts Aeblus and Aznar, Frankish vassals from the Duchy of Vasconia sent by the new King of Aquitaine, Pepin, were captured by the joint forces of Iñigo Arista and the Banu Qasi.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Before Pepin's death, emperor Louis had appointed a new king in 832, his son Charles the Bald, while the Aquitanian lords elected Pepin II as king.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] This struggle for control of the kingdom led to a constant period of war between Charles, loyal to his father and the Carolingian power, and Pepin II, who relied more on the support of Basque and Aquitanian lords.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Despite the early conquest of southern Gaul by the Franks after the Battle of Vouillé in 507, the Frankish element was feeble south of the Loire, where Gothic and Gallo-Roman Law prevailed and a small Frankish settlement took place.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] However scarce, some Frankish population and nobles settled down in regions like Albigeois, Carcassonne (on the fringes of Septimania), Toulouse, and Provence and Lower Rhone (the last two not in Aquitaine).
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] After the death of the king Dagobert I, the Merovingian tenure south of the Loire became largely nominal, with the actual power being in the hands of autonomous regional leaders and counts.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The Franks may have become largely assimilated to the preponderant Gallo-Roman culture by the 8th century, but their names were well in use by the ruling class, like Odo.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Still, in the Battle of Toulouse, the Aquitanian duke Odo the Great was said to be leading an army of Aquitanians and Franks.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] On the other hand, the Franks did not mix with the Basques, keeping separate paths.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In the periods before and after the Muslim thrust, the Basques are often cited in several accounts stirring against Frankish attempts to subdue Aquitaine (stretching up to Toulouse) and Vasconia, pointing to a not preponderant but clearly significant Basque presence in the former too.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Recorded evidence points to their deployment across Aquitaine in a military capacity as a mainstay of the Duke's forces.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] 'Romans' are cited as living in the cities of Aquitaine, as opposed to the Franks (mid 8th century).
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] After the 843 Treaty of Verdun, the defeat of Pepin II of Aquitaine and the death of Charles the Bald, the Kingdom of Aquitaine (subsumed in West Francia) ceased to have any relevance and the title of King of Aquitaine took on a nominal value.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In 1058, the Duchy of Vasconia (Gascony) and Aquitaine merged under the rule of William VIII, Duke of Aquitaine.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The title "Duke of Aquitaine" was held by the counts of Poitiers from the 10th to the 12th century.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Aquitaine passed to France in 1137 when the duchess Eleanor of Aquitaine married Louis VII of France, but their marriage was annulled in 1152.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] When Eleanor's new husband became King Henry II of England in 1154, the area became an English possession, and a cornerstone of the Angevin Empire.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Aquitaine remained English until the end of the Hundred Years' War in 1453, when it was annexed by France.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] During the three hundred years that the region was ruled by the Kings of England, links between Aquitaine and England strengthened, with large quantities of wine produced in southwestern France being exported to London, Southampton, and other English ports.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In fact, so much wine and other produce was being exported to London and sold that by the start of the Hundred Years' War the profits from Aquitaine were the principal source of the English King's income per annum.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The region served as a stronghold for the Protestant Huguenots during the 16th and 17th centuries, who suffered persecution at the hands of the French Catholics.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The Huguenots called upon the English crown for assistance against forces led by Cardinal Richelieu.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] From the 13th century until the French Revolution, Aquitaine was usually known as Guyenne.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Aquitaine consists of 3,150,890 inhabitants, equivalent to 6% of the total French population.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The region of Aquitaine forms the 6th most populated region in France.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] French is the official language of the region.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Many residents also have some knowledge of Basque, of a variety of Occitan (Gascon, Limousin, or Languedocien), or of the Poitevin-Saintongeais dialect of French.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] In 2005, 78,000 children were learning Occitan as a second language in state schools and 2,000 were enrolled in Occitan-medium private schools.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Bordeaux is the largest city in Aquitaine.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] It is a port city on the Garonne River in the Gironde department.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] It is the capital of Aquitaine, as well as the prefecture of the Gironde department.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Bordeaux is famous for its wine industry.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Apart from Bordeaux, there are also other important cities in Aquitaine.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] The region is home to many successful sports teams.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Rugby union is particularly popular in the region.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Bull-fighting is also popular in the region.
[src:artificialization/aquitaine] Major surfing championships regularly take place on Aquitaine's coast.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] It is generally accompanied by a loss of self-healing capacity on the part of the environment (reduced ecological resilience).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Artificialization is often summed up as the disappearance of natural spaces under concrete or bitumen, during the construction of buildings (apartment blocks, hotels, houses, shops, industries, parking lots) or transport networks.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] While soil sealing is a huge part of land artificialisation, more generally, it takes place when natural environments are heavily transformed by man.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] It could also be mentioned the areas developed for military purposes (military testing grounds, underground tunnels, fortifications, glacis, no-man's-land, etc.).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In Europe in 2015, the surface area of sealed land exceeded one million square kilometers, i.e.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] 2.3% of the European Union's surface area and 200 m² per inhabitant (over 50,000 km2 and 9.4% of the territory in France).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] On average, 165 ha, or 1,650,000 m² of natural environments and farmland, are destroyed every day in France and replaced by roads, housing, and business parks, as part of the urban sprawl phenomenon.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Between 2005 and 2015, this represented almost 6,000 km², the size of a département in ten years.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] One of the aims of the French Green and Blue Network (TVB or Schéma régional de cohérence écologique) is to limit this phenomenon and mitigate its consequences.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Since 2018, the goal of Zero Net Artificialization has been a major roadmap in the fight against artificialization.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] This was followed by larger-scale developments, often designed for the intensive exploitation of water from the great rivers (Nile, Tigris, Euphrates...).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In Europe, beaver dams (and the beavers themselves, hunted for their meat and fur), which maintained water reserves and open riparian habitats, were destroyed.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] At the same time, the construction of fords, then bridges, dykes, mills, and systems for impounding and regulating watercourses and for drainage spread, culminating in major episodes of polderization, etc.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] At the same time, the urbanization of the region increased.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] At the same time, urbanization expanded, supported by networks of roads and trading centers (e.g. the Silk Road).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Peri-urban waste dumps appeared, gradually buried beneath the urban sprawl.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Cemeteries, monuments, and fortifications (e.g. the Great Wall of China) are accompanied by vast clearing, leveling, and earthworks (terraces, embankments, sunken paths, low walls).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] During the Anthropocene, the development of coal mines, the oil industry, railroads, automobiles, and tractors led to more intensive farming.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] This accelerated the anthropization of the landscape and subsoil, colonized by millions of kilometers of cables, pipes, and sewers, including in the colonies of wealthy countries on every continent.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The network of roads, freeways, and railroads is expanding, as are industrial, commercial, sports, and sometimes military facilities.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] At the end of the twentieth century, the pace of artificialization accelerated even further and is visible on satellite imagery.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Some areas are particularly hard hit: a large part of the coastline and estuaries of many countries has been artificialized by the construction of seaside resorts, coastal road networks, and port facilities.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Cities and their outskirts, as well as all agricultural environments, and all ancient forests in temperate countries and then in most tropical countries (with the exception of a few protected massifs).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Artificialization is moving towards developing countries, with peri-urbanization particularly marked in the vicinity of megacities and urban metropolises (in France, for example, the Île-de-France and Toulouse).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In wealthy countries, it's often linked to the success of the single-family home, which is also reflected in urban sprawl and peri-urbanization.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The French urban planning code defines artificialisation as "the lasting alteration of all or part of a soil's ecological functions, in particular its biological, hydric and climatic functions, as well as its agronomic potential by its occupation or use".
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In 2006, 8.3% of mainland France was affected by land artificialisation, a figure that rose to 9.4% in 2015.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In fifty years, seven million hectares of land have been buried for housing (40%), the economy (30%: businesses, warehouses, shops), and transport infrastructure (30%).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Since 2009, 90% of land artificialisation has been at the expense of fertile soils.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] According to Corine Land Cover statistics on land use in France, the French region with the least amount of artificial land is Corsica, with 2.1% of its surface area, while Île-de-France tops the list with 21.6%.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Artificialization is highly polarized at the national level.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] A study by the Cerema (the French Environment and Spatial Planning Agency) reveals a high level of artificialisation on the coast and around medium-sized towns and cities.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In July 2019, annual data on a municipal scale for the period 2009-2017 were published, and have been updated annually since.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In 2015 and 2016, it was estimated that the phenomenon had "stabilized" (at 9.3% of mainland France) thanks to the 2008 crisis, which slowed land artificialisation (to +0.8% per year).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Recent data, however, confirm a resumption of the phenomenon since 2016: after a period of decline between 2011 and 2016, artificialisation is again increasing its pace, reaching 23,454 ha between 2016 and 2017.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In 2022, the Cerema dashboard reveals that 21,079 ha have been taken or pre-empted in 2021 in France on natural and agricultural spaces, almost 1,200 ha more than in 2020, but almost 1,300 ha less than in 2019.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Despite this upturn, the Senate majority is calling for a moratorium on the application of the 2021 Climate and Resilience Act, tabling bills to extend deadlines and pointing to the lack of financial resources dedicated to achieving the goal of zero net artificialization.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In June 2022, the Association des maires de France (AMF) lodged an appeal with the Conseil d'État against two decrees implementing this law.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Christophe Béchu, Minister of Ecological Transition and Territorial Cohesion, has said he is open to rewriting some of the decrees.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In 2009, according to the Institut français de l'environnement (IFEN), land artificialisation increased by 60,000 ha per year (or 6,000 km2 in ten years, equivalent to the size of the Seine-et-Marne département).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The 885 coastal municipalities are particularly hard hit.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Despite the "natural" and rural areas spared thanks to the *Conservatoire du littoral* and the Littoral law, less than 500 m from the sea, the rate of artificialization (28.2% of the territory artificialized on average) is 5.5 times higher than the average for metropolitan France.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The coastlines of Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Pays de la Loire, Languedoc-Roussillon, and PACA are the most artificialized by construction, while those of Normandy, Brittany and Poitou-Charentes are artificialized by agriculture.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] According to Jean-François Doulet, in the 2010s, the urbanized surface area in China almost quadrupled from the early 1980s to 2012.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Artificialization was estimated in 2012 to be equivalent to twice the surface area of the Île-de-France region each year, and a 15-year estimate is for a surface area equivalent to the current urbanized area of Europe.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Urbanization leads to the creation of suburban areas, housing estates, and towns.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In terms of global warming, artificial surfaces, usually dark in color, affect albedo by absorbing solar radiation and emitting long-wave infrared radiation.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] This radiation is reflected to Earth by greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, contributing to global warming.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] This artificialization may have an impact on the local climate, by increasing surface temperatures (LST), as shown by the satellite image of surface temperature measurement opposite.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] According to the IPCC's Sixth Assessment Report, reducing vegetation affects the local and adjacent climate through the subsequent disruption of the water cycle).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Climate balances are complex and closely linked to the properties of physical surfaces, which also have biological functions.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In particular, living organisms have developed strategies for capturing and storing water.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Examples include the role of Pseudomonas syringae as a nucleating agent, the effect of earthworm galleries on water infiltration in soils, or the effect of glomalin production by fungi on soil compaction.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] They are capable of producing aerosols to initiate condensation, or releasing water vapor so that the ambient air reaches the dew point and nucleates rain droplets.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Thus, the disruption of an ecosystem, which is often at equilibrium, leads to a less efficient system, which will tend to heat up more, as evaporating water allows cooling.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] This is illustrated by infrared satellite observations of a deforested area in Brazil, around Jaru, compared with anthropized areas and pristine surfaces.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In the Jaru area, less heat is evacuated by evapotranspiration, as the albedo has increased due to changes in land use.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Warmer soils then disrupt local precipitation as, for example, rainfall volatilizes as it reaches the ground.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Volumes of water lost through runoff (or conveyed by man) are not evapotranspired and are not received by areas further out on the continent.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Cities, through the heat islands they form, modify the volume and intensity of precipitation.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] It is therefore possible to see the location of certain cities on a precipitation map.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] It is possible to see storm fronts cease activity close to cities while continuing on either side and resuming further out.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Conversely, reducing the gap between hot and cold spots can significantly improve the climate, as demonstrated by an observational and modeling study of climate conditions in the Corn Belt region of the USA.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] This area takes its name from the high density of corn grown there.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Temperature trends over the period 1970–2020 are comparatively negative compared with the period 1910–1950 (−0.35 °C), while warming is observable around the area.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] By climatic mechanisms, precipitation increases in this area.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] A comparison between the results obtained by global modeling and those obtained by a smaller-scale model demonstrates the relevance of implementing models that are correctly parameterized and truly reflect surface properties (in this case, the right percentage of maize).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In addition, numerous studies have shown that the artificialization of natural environments leads to a loss of biodiversity and changes in the functional composition of biotopes, a loss that is associated with a reduction in the productivity and stability of ecosystems.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] From the point of view of ecology and landscape ecology, the artificialization of landscapes, environments, and biotopes is one of the factors contributing to the ecological fragmentation of natural habitats and the qualitative degradation of landscapes.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] It is one of the factors used to calculate the eco-potentiality of a plot, region, or landscape element.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] It is also a factor in homogenization (genetic, taxonomic, and functional), which is highly unfavorable to the maintenance of biodiversity.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] By favoring ubiquitous species to the detriment of much more varied specialist species, anthropogenic homogenization of life (Biotic homogenization) has serious immediate and future consequences for ecological and evolutionary processes.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Some artificial environments (such as certain quarries and slag heaps), because they have received neither fertilizers nor pesticides, may nevertheless be home to processes characterized by a high degree of naturalness.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Semi-natural environments are also used to designate environments that have been artificially altered, but can still act as a substitute habitat for some of the species in a given biogeographical zone (e.g. meadows, hedgerows, and certain extensively managed forests, such as the "prosilva" type).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] It also concerns the nocturnal environment, disturbed by artificial lighting (light pollution).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] From an agronomist's point of view, soil artificialization leads to a loss of humus and carbon, a reduced water retention capacity, and, consequently, a loss of fertility, aggravating the phenomena of erosion and soil degradation.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In the long term, this leads to a loss of natural and agricultural resources, in addition to the loss of arable land to built-up or waterproofed areas (although some greenhouse crops are grown on artificial soil, or even without any soil at all, using hydroponics).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Quantifying artificialization involves comparing land use data.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The law of December 30, 2006, on the preservation of water resources and aquatic environments allows municipalities to introduce a tax on impervious surfaces.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Agricultural land is the hardest hit, which is why the French Agricultural Modernization Act of July 27, 2010, aims to halve the rate of consumption of agricultural land over ten years (2010-2020), aided by the Departmental Commissions for the Consumption of Agricultural Spaces (CDCEA) it sets up.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] However, the 2012 Environmental Conference was less ambitious, aiming only to slow down the artificialization of land (to achieve stability by 2025).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Some regional climate-air-energy plans (SRCAE) include quantified targets, such as that of the Nord-Pas-de-Calais region (a threefold reduction in the rate of land development).
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In parallel with its Trame Verte et Bleue, in 2006 the region experimented with a regional planning directive aimed at combating the artificialization of the territory through peri-urbanization.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] She also suggests ways of making taxation more conducive to less artificial development.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] This platform also makes annual and municipal data on French territory accessible, enabling external stakeholders to better understand the issue.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In the same year, a National Observatory of Soil Artificialization was established.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The Minister for Ecological and Inclusive Transition commissioned a foresight mission to *France Stratégie* to outline scenarios for achieving the ZAN target and to identify ways to protect natural, agricultural, and forested areas.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The resulting report, authored by biologist Julien Fosse, was made public on July 23, 2019, and presented to Emmanuelle Wargon and Julien Denormandie.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The public think tank proposed measures to achieve zero net land take by 2030, focusing on reducing gross artificialization through higher-density new constructions and restoring abandoned artificialized lands.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] In 2021, the Climate and Resilience Act, under its section titled "Housing," set a goal to halve the rate of land take over the next decade compared to the previous one, to achieve zero net artificialization by 2050.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The law also prohibits the construction of new large retail spaces, with exceptions for sales areas under 10,000 square meters.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] Following directives on water and air, the proposed framework directive for soil protection aimed to address soil degradation and erosion across Europe.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The European Commission introduced the directive in September 2006, and it was adopted in the first reading by the European Parliament on November 14, 2007.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] However, it was blocked the following year by five countries—France, Germany, the United Kingdom, Austria, and the Netherlands—preventing a qualified majority.
[src:artificialization/artificialization] The directive was ultimately abandoned in 2014.
